<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Jobless Claims Increase to 5-Month High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The number of American
workers filing first-time claims for jobless benefits reached the
highest level in more than five months, the U.S. Labor Department
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the jobless claims shot up by 22,000
last week ending December 28 of last year. The new applications
for unemployment insurance totaled a seasonally adjusted 366,000,
up from a revised 344,000 during the week ending December 21.
</P>
<P>
It was the highest level of new jobless claims in the U.S.
since they totaled 367,000 during the week ending July 13.
</P>
<P>
The increase of 22,000 jobless claims was also the biggest jump
since they shot up by 23,000 at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
The four-week moving average of new weekly jobless claims rose
by 9,000 to 352,500, the highest since 360,500 on July 13.
</P>
<P>
Many U.S. analysts prefer to track the less-volatile four-week
average because it smooths out the spikes in the weekly reports.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. unemployment rate has been increasing in the past few
months. After dipping to 5.1 percent in August, the unemployment
rate grew to 5.4 percent in November, the highest since an
identical jobless rate last July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
