<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Forces Continue Cross-Border Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish security forces are
continuing their cross-border military operation in a bid to
destroy the military bases of the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) in northern Iraq, the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that Turkish F-4 fighters, which took off from
the air base in Diyarbakir, southeastern Turkey, bombarded Hakurk
camp, one of the largest PKK camps in Sinath region and over 10
kilometers deep into northern Iraq this morning in the continued
cross-border operation, which have lasted for three days.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the Turkish security forces killed many
PKK militants, but failed to give the figure.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Turkish fighters started to bombard three PKK
camps in Sinath region and about 5,000 Turkish ground troops
and village guards began to attack the PKK militants, who tried
to flee from Sindi throat in northern Iraq under the cover
of Cobra helicopters.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued Wednesday by the General Staff
of the Turkish Armed Forces, the Turkish security forces killed 72
PKK rebels in the past two days of the cross-border operation.
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops have entered northern Iraq for several times in
order to wipe out the PKK militants, who intermittently launch
cross-border attacks against Turkish military and civilian
targets.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government, which has been deprived of the control
over the northern Kurdish area by the U.S.-led western forces, has
made protests against the Turkish operations before and accused
Turkey of violating its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a guerrilla war for autonomy,
which has claimed more than 21,000 lives in southeastern Turkey
since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
