<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat-Netanyahu Summit Likely Today, Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is
expected to meet today, but they may not sign the Hebron deal,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai held an eight-hour
meeting with Palestinian senior officials Abu Mazen throughout
the night at the Herzliya home of U.S. Ambassador Martin Indyk
in the presence of U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The talks was held after the terrorist shooting in Hebron
earlier Wednesday in which an Israeli soldier shot and wounded
seven Palestinians in the central Market. Both sides condemned
the terrorist act and promised to continue the ongoing peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said after the talks that an Arafat-Netanyahu
summit would possibly be held late today, but several outstanding
issues remained to be resolved before the Hebron agreement could
be signed.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the Palestinian side should not try to
reopen talks on issues that have been closed. Israeli officials
feared that the Palestinian side might make new demands for
security reasons following the shooting incident Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Currently, issues of concern to the Palestinians include
obtaining a firm date for the last Israeli troop pullback from
the West Bank, the gradual release of prisoners and a Palestinian
presence at the Tomb of Patriachs, the holy shrine for both Jews
and Moslems.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side especially insisted on its demand for
joint patrol near the holy shrine in order to protect the safety
of Palestinian worshipers. Hebron, where 450 Jewish settlers
live among 120,000 Palestinians, has been a hotbed for
Israeli-Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
Before the Wednesday shooting, a Jewish settler named Baruch
Goldstein killed 29 Palestinian worshipers and wounded dozens of
other in a similar shooting spree in February 1994 at the Tomb
of Patriachs.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman, who is now visiting India,
stressed the urgency of speedy conclusion of the long-delayed
agreement on Israeli troop pullback from Hebron. He asked
Mordechai Wednesday to convey a message to Arafat to express
regret for the shooting incident which he described as "a stupid
and wicked act."
</P>
<P>
Ross acted quickly after the Wednesday shooting by holding
separate meetings with Netanyahu and Arafat to offset the
possible repercussion of the incident on the Hebron talks. He
said the incident underscored quick action on concluding a deal
on Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton telephoned Arafat Wednesday to
express "outrage and sadness" at the incident. Israeli sources
said that during their phone conversation, Clinton urged Arafat to
wrap up the Hebron talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
