<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's 1996 Oil Export Income Probably To Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Higher price sustained by excess
demand in the world market may have boosted the oil income of Nigeria
and other oil exporting countries in the past year.
</P>
<P>
The oil export revenue of Nigeria and other 10 members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries for 1996 is projected
to increase 23 percent to 162.68 billion U.s. dollars on a
year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
A market report reaching here today estimates Nigeria may have
grossed about 14.09 billion dollars from the export of over two
million barrels per day of oil and condensate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
About 13.18 billion dollars of Nigeria's oil revenues are expected
to have gone to the federal government, which is 3.46 billion dollars
more than the projected 9.72 billion dollars in last year's government
budget.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in September last year, Nigeria's Finance Minister Chief
Anthony Ani reported that a total of 5.03 billion dollars had been
earned from the oil sector by June, compared with a targeted sum of
3.94 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil accounts for more than 90 percent of Nigeria's total
exports. Recently there has been fear of a likely drop in the price of
oil in the international market this year as Iraq is to resume oil
exports.
</P>
<P>
To change the overdependence on oil export for foreign exchange,
the Nigerian government has over the recent years been encouraging the
promotion of non-oil export. But little effect has been produced so
far.
</P>
<P>
It is expected the government will continue to give a boost to the
development on non-oil sectors by new incentives expected to be
included in this year's budget, which is reported to come before the
public next week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
