<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Economists Predict Slower Growth in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economy will be
coasting at a slower growth rate this year than in 1996 while
heading into its seventh straight year of expansion, U.S.
economists predicted in a semiannual survey by The Wall Street
Journal.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported today that it is the consensus of 57
economists participating in the latest survey.
</P>
<P>
With an annual growth rate of the gross domestic product (GDP)
at 2.9 percent in the first three quarters of 1996, the economists
are looking for a modest slowdown in GDP growth in 1997. They
predicted an annual rate of 2 percent in both the first and second
halves of this year.
</P>
<P>
A sharp change in short-term interest rates that would either
stymie or stimulate the economy is unlikely this year, they said.
The vast majority don't expect the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) to
change rates when its policy-maker meets in February.
</P>
<P>
The key is low inflation, they said. The consumer price index
(CPI) was running at a year-to-year growth rate of 3.2 percent in
November. But the core inflation, minus volatile food and energy
components, was running at only a 2.6 percent rate in the month.
</P>
<P>
The economists are looking for an annual CPI growth rate of 2.9
percent in May as the unemployment rate slips a bit to 5.3 percent
from its recent 5.4 percent level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most economists surveyed said that the heavy
personal debt of U.S. consumers will slow consumer spending, which
in turn will take some of the lift out of corporate profits and
capital spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
