<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Again Blames PA for Delaying Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel today blamed the
Palestinian Authority (PA) for delaying the signing of a
long-projected Hebron agreement as the hope for an
Israeli-Palestinian summit faded away once again.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators struggled today to arrange
a summit between Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and
PA President Yasser Arafat, but failed to iron out the final
details on reaching the Hebron agreement.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Ilan, Netanyahu's media adviser, blamed the PA for
applying the old tactics of footdragging in order to bring
more international pressure on Israel so as to squeeze out more
concessions.
</P>
<P>
"It's quite clear that the stalling is done by the Palestinian
Authority. The reasonable guess is that this situation of no
agreement favors them and it's detrimental to us that most of the
world tend to blame Israel for not doing something that was
supposed to do," he told the Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Palestinian side had put forward new demands
during the talks, Bar-Ilan said that Israel would not agree
to reopen issues that have already been closed.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the Palestinian side agreed, Israel would
sign the Hebron deal immediately, or even two months ago. He
warned that any delay would increase tension and threats to
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Following the Wednesday violence in Hebron in which
an Israeli soldier shot and wounded seven Palestinians, the
urgency for a speedy conclusion of Hebron deal increased.
</P>
<P>
Bar-Ilan said earlier that he expected the Arafat-Netanyahu
summit to take place late today to initial the Hebron deal. For
the past week, an Arafat-Netanyahu summit was virtually expected
every day to sign the deal, but each time the hope faded away.
</P>
<P>
This could be repeated today. PA Cabinet Secretary Nabil
Abu Rudeineh today said that the Hebron talks would likely
extend for several more days to resolve the last issues
blocking the repeatedly-delayed agreement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's deputy Abu Mazen, who held an eight-hour meeting with
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai overnight Wednesday,
revealed that there was still one issue remained to be settled
before signing the deal, that is, the timetable for further
Israeli redeployments in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai briefed Netanyahu today on his meeting with Mazen and
 held several discussions with U.S. special envoy Dennis Ross in
a bid to find out ways of clearing the last obstacles.
</P>
<P>
Ross is to meet with Arafat late this evening in an effort to
finalize the long-delayed Hebron agreement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Arafat held a meeting with European Union
peace envoy Miguel Angel Moratinos to discuss the current
situation of Hebron talks. Asked if he would meet Netanyahu
today, Arafat replied: "Who knows?"  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
