<HEADLINE> Drug Smuggling Truck Detained by Ugandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 2 (Xinhua) --The Ugandan authorities detained
a truck suspected carrying mandrake tablets worth five million
U.S.Dollars, the local daily '' New Vision'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
The destination of the drug is unknown, but the drug has a
high resale value in South Africa and Zambia, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The consignments were shipped from Bombay,India.
</P>
<P>
altogether two trucks were
intercepted in a recent operation, but one of the trucks
suspected carrying similar goods mysteriously vanished when the
other was detained, said the report quoting the investigators.
</P>
<P>
Two Uganda-based Asian businessmen allegedly involved in the
case have fled to Nairobi after learning about the seizure of the
truck.
</P>
<P>
Mandrake is a prohibited drug working on central nervous
system and its tablet form is very popular in South Africa.
Mandrake were often smuggled into South Africa via Tanzania and
Mozambique to exchange it for motor parts. 
