<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capsized Cargo Ship Sinks in Aegean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Athens, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Greek cargo ship the Dystos,
which capsized last Saturday off the Aegean island of Evia, sank
today to a depth of 32 meters, harbor officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Greek-flagged freighter was carrying 5,700 tons of cement
when it was engulfed by two large waves, causing it to list and
its cargo shifted.
</P>
<P>
The ship had 21 people on board, 18 crew and three passengers.
Only one person, 22-year-old trainee officer Christos Anagnostou,
was rescued.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen bodies have been recovered to date, while three more
seamen were still missing and presumed dead. The search for the
three is continuing.
</P>
<P>
The boat was spotted by rescue teams almost 10 hours after a
Spanish maritime station picked up its emergency signal.
</P>
<P>
Five port authority officers were suspended pending
investigation into possible negligence over the handling of search
and rescue operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
