<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Major Auto Makers Forecast Sales for 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Major auto makers in the United
States have forecast that the year 1997 will turn out much like
last year when auto sales were on a strong and stable trend.
</P>
<P>
Alex Trotman, chairman, chief executive and president of the
Ford Motor Company, predicted that for 1997 overall industry sales
will reach 15 million to 15.5 million passenger cars, pickup
trucks, sport utility vehicles, mini-vans and heavier trucks.
</P>
<P>
The General Motor Corporation and the Chrysler Corporation
echoed his forecast which was based on an assumption that
unemployment and inflation would remain low and the American
economy would continue to produce jobs at a brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
But auto executives and economists for the Big Three automakers
have expressed concern about whether auto sales will stay strong,
for, according to a New York Times report today, the auto market
is quite sensitive to the performance of the overall economy. "For
decades, few industries have been as cyclical as the automobile
business, with sales soaring in good times and plunging so deeply
in bad times that very few survival of some auto makers has been
threatened," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Economists and executives said the threat of economic
turbulence caused by unpredictable events remain. "I expect there
will be, in the next five years, a downturn," Trotman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
