<HEADLINE> Traffic Death Toll Breaches 1,000 Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johannesburg, January 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 people have
been killed in traffic accidents throughout South Africa since the
traditional holiday season began on December 3 last year, the
National Traffici Information Center (NTIC) announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A NTIC report said head-on collisions, collisions with
pedestrians and vehicles overturning continue to be the main causes
of fatalities.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show the death toll in provinces of Eastern Cape and
Western Cape are well above the average caused by collisions while
pedestrian fatalities in Gauteng Province are much higher than the
national average, the report said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is administratively divided into nine provinces. In
addition to violences and diseases, traffic accidents have been said
to be one of the major killers to South Africans.
</P>
<P>
NTIC officials and informed sources said a large number of traffic
policemen have been mobilized to patrol on major streets and
freeways to decrease traffic toll.
</P>
<P>
However, despite traffic authorities' sustained efforts, the
phenomina of overspeed driving and drunk-driving, the major causes of
traffic accidents, are still quite popular in the country. enditem


