<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 115 PKK Rebels Killed in Turkey's Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- One hundred and fifteen rebels
of the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) were killed in military
operations both in northern Iraq and southeastern Turkey,
according to the semi-official Anatolia News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that Turkish security forces had wiped out 101
PKK militants after the country's air and ground forces attacked
the camps of the rebel group in the Sinath region, over 10
kilometers deep into northern Iraq in their three-day successive
cross-border military operations.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the security forces had also killed 14
PKK members in the anti-PKK maneuvers in Nusaybin town in Mardin
province bordering Syria.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security forces staged the cross-border operations
Monday night in a bid to destroy the PKK military bases in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security men continuously bombarded four PKK camps
in the Sinath region and about 5,000 government troops and
village guards attacked the PKK militants who tried to flee from
northern Iraq under the cover of Cobra helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Turkish security forces have crossed into northern Iraq for
several times in a bid to wipe out the PKK guerrillas who
launched cross-border raids against Turkish military and civilian
targets.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government, which has lost control over northern
Iraq, an area held by Kurds backed by allied-forces, has made
protests against the Turkish operations before, accusing Turkey
of violation of its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Turkish government troops killed 13,255 rebels,
wounded 244 and captured about 2,000, according to official
figures.
</P>
<P>
Over 21,000 people including PKK rebels, civilians and
government troops have been killed in conflicts since August
1984 when the outlawed group started separatist activities for
self-rule in southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
