<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Young Swimmers to Compete in World Cup in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- "Although they are young, they
are part of China's best. Let's see how they can do at the World
Cup meet here," a Chinese swimming coach said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiong, deputy head coach of the Chinese national swimming
team, talked to reporters after the Chinese team arrived at the
Kai Tak airport this afternoon for the coming Epson Swimming World
Cup Hong Kong '97, the opening leg of this year's eight-leg World
Cup short course swimming series.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 13-swimmer team are teenagers, among whom are such
Olympians as female swimmers Nian Yun, 14, and Chen Yan, 17.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the main purpose of his team here is to have
the younger ones tested for getting mature.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that it's hard for some of the national team's
veteran members to hang on till the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000.
</P>
<P>
"We have to get ourselves ready as early as possible for the
Games," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang revealed that all the Chinese swimmers participating in
the Hong Kong meet will return to Beijing to join other members of
the national team for the second leg of the World Cup series.
</P>
<P>
And some of the national team's elite members are to be sent to
the six European stops of the series in such cities as Espoo of
Finland, Malmo of Sweden and Paris.
</P>
<P>
As for the national swimming team, the Eight National Games
scheduled for October in Shanghai is the number one event on the
year's calendar. "We have to arrange our training and
competitions with priority left on the Games," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also said that some of the current team here would be
part of an elite task force which sets its sight on Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the performance by a relatively young team at last
summer's Olympic Games in Atlanta, Zhang said that the swimmers
did what they could, although short of somewhat too high an
expectation from home.
</P>
<P>
With only three of the 21 Olympic swimmers from the last
Olympics, Zhang said it was almost impossible for them to achieve
what Chinese swimmers had at Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
The current young swimmers are really doing well, both in
training and competitions so far, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
"But they need to go through more hardship and major test,
especially through international competitions," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
"That's the only way to get mature," he added.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Hong Kong meet starts on Saturday. A record-setting
entry of 28 teams is to be fielded, according to the organizers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
