<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Forces Continue Bombardment in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli occupation forces
continued today bombardment at suspected guerrilla targets in a
mountain area opposite the Israeli self-proclaimed "security
zone" in south Lebanon, but no casualties were reported by
security sources in the area.
</P>
<P>
The bombardment was accompanied by reconnaissance flights of
Israeli warplanes over the last active battlefront of the
Arab-Israeli conflict, the Lebanese security sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli forces concentrated today's bombardment, which
lasted from the morning to the evening, at Iglim Al-Toffah, a
ridge often used by guerrillas of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or
Party of God, as a springboard to launch attacks at Israel's
buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
At 9:10 a.m. (07:10 GMT), the Israeli troops in their
positions on hills overlooking the south Lebanese village of
Baraashit swept vicinities of the village with heavy machinegun
fire.
</P>
<P>
Twenty minutes later, Israeli artillery fired its first
volley of smoking bombs at Jebal Al-Rafih in Iglim Al-Toffah,
some 60 kilometers southeast of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The bombardment was extended to the villages of Sejoud and
Rihan, then to Wadi Slouqi, Zibgin, Wadi Marimin and other areas.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Resistance, the military wing of the Shiite
fundamentalist Hezbollah, announced that its fighters attacked
the Israeli outpost of Balat at 12:30 a.m. (10:30 GMT) with
anti-tank rockets and machineguns.
</P>
<P>
It said in a statement that another squad of its fighters
detonated a mine on the Deir Siryan road in the middle sector of
south Lebanon, targeting a foot patrol of the Israeli-backed
South Lebanon Army (SLA) militia, killing and wounding several
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the SLA militia confirmed that one militiaman was
killed and two others were wounded in the bombing attack.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Resistance also said that its guerrillas attacked
the Israeli position of Dabsheh with "suitable weapons" and
caused casualties to the enemy.
</P>
<P>
Hit-and-run attacks by Moslem guerrillas and bombardments by
Israeli forces constitute a daily scene in south Lebanon, where
the Jewish state established the 1,100-square-kilometer buffer
zone in 1985 in a bid to protect northern Israel from
cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Hezbollah said today that it
carried out 37 military operations against Israeli occupation
forces and their client militia in south Lebanon in December
1996.
</P>
<P>
It said that three Israeli soldiers were killed and six
others were wounded, including Brigadier General Eli Amitai,
Israel's chief liaison officer and commander of the 1,000 troops
garrisoned in south Lebanon, who was slightly injured twice by
blasts of roadside bombs.
</P>
<P>
One SLA militiaman was shot dead and two others were injured
by Israeli forces when the three were attempting to defect from
their post of Hola, the Iranian-backed Moslem group said.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah issued today its statistics on Israeli casualties
in clashes with Lebanese guerrillas in 1996, saying that 45
Israelis were killed and 211 others were wounded, including one
Jewish settler killed and 92 others injured by Katyusha rockets
fired into northern Israel in the first months of this year.
</P>
<P>
It added that its fighters carried out 765 military operations
in the whole year, during which 34 SLA militiamen were also
killed and 72 others wounded, with the Islamic Resistance
suffering a loss of 47 lives.
</P>
<P>
Israel admitted that 28 Israeli soldiers were killed and 102
others were wounded in guerrilla operations against its forces,
and two soldiers died and two others injured in different
incidents in the occupied enclave in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
It also confirmed that 20 SLA militiamen were killed and 58
others wounded.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,500 SLA militiamen collaborating with the Jewish
state are patrolling the Israeli self-styled "security zone" in
south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
