<HEADLINE> Tunisia Strives to Attract Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- With the advent of the new year,
Tunisia will establish contacts with 500 external establishments
to attract foreign investments, sources at the Tunisian Ministry
of International Cooperation and Investment said today.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that among the foreign establishments 300
are in Europe and 200 non-European ones.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, attention will be paid to the markets of three Asian
states, namely, Japan, South Korea and Malaysia, as well as Arab
markets particularly in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The sources pointed out that apart from these measures,
Tunisia will endeavor to mobilize all potentials to invite the
largest possible amount of foreign investments in 1997.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this, an estimated 470,000 Tunisian dinars (about
470,000 U.S. dollars) has been earmarked for the organization of
symposiums, regional and international economic seminars, video
and tape-making and publications in several languages, and
information discs, so as to make foreign investors acquainted
with the investment climate and opportunities in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the total foreign financial resources,
which have flown into Tunisia during the 1992-1996 plan period,
have reached about 5,064 million dinars (about 5,064 million
dollars), of which 1,194 million dinars (about 1,194 million
dollars) came in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
