<HEADLINE> AL Urges Dialogue to Settle Sudan-Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) today expressed
deep concern about the recent developments in eastern Sudan, a day
after Sudan accused Eritrea of downing its chopper and attacking
its gunship.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo-based AL, in a statement issued today, called for
handling the issue through dialogue and on the basis of good
neighborliness and non-interference with the internal affairs of
other countries.
</P>
<P>
Sudan had lodged a note with the AL's General Secretariat on
the dangers confronting eastern Sudan due to foreign interference.
</P>
<P>
Sudan said Wednesday that the missile that hit a Sudanese
helicopter gunship had been fired from an Eritrean army camp near
the Sudanese-Eritrean borders.
</P>
<P>
It also accused Eritrea of shooting down a Sudanese military
plane and killing all its passengers.
</P>
<P>
Sudan charged that that Eritrea was still staging a flagrant
attack, vowing to use all means to defend itself.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea is the base of Sudanese opposition movement against
the Sudanese government led by President Omar el-Bashir.
</P>
<P>
In a speech today on the occasion of the 41st anniversary of
Sudan's independence, Bashir called on the opposition to
relinquish armed hostilities and join the peace process launched
eight months ago with the signing to the Political Charter for
Peace.
</P>
<P>
He, however, made no allusion to either reported attacks by
Eritrea on Sudanese territory or to the escape of Sadek al-Mahdi,
leader of the opposition Ummah party, to join the opposition
groups abroad.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today held talks with Mahdi, who arrived here Friday for a 10-day
visit on the first leg of his three-month Arab and European tour.
</P>
<P>
It is the second meeting between Mubarak and a Sudanese
opposition leader within four days. The Egyptian president Monday
met with Mohamed Othman al-Merghani, leader of the Sudanese
Democratic Alliance, which is the gathering of Sudanese opposition
parties working in exile.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, Mahdi slipped out of Khartoum to Eritrea, the
base of Sudanese opposition movement against the Sudanese
government led by President Omar Hassan al-Bashir, who ousted
Mahdi in 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
