<HEADLINE> Writethru: S'pore's Ruling PAP Wins All But Two Seats in General Election (1)  by Zeng Hu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 3 (Xinhua) -- After declaring its victory in
the hotly-contested seats of the Cheng San Group Representation
Constituency (GRC) Friday morning, Singapore's ruling People's
Action Party finally won all but two seats in the 83-member
parliament in this general election.
</P>
<P>
In the Cheng San GRC, the five-member PAP team, led by
Education Minister Lee Yock Suan, secured 53,553 votes, or 54.8
percent of the total votes cast in the ward. They defeated the
Workers' Party team, headed by its secretary-general J.B.
Jeyaretnam, by a big margin of 9,421 votes.
</P>
<P>
All in all, the PAP has won about 65 percent of the votes in
the contested constituencies, up by about four percentage points
from the 61 percent supportive rate of the last general election
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing shortly after the final result was
announced, Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said he was satisfied with
the outcome of the election, as voters had rejected the Workers'
Party and Tang Liang Hong, a Workers' Party candidate in the Cheng
San GRC who was accused by the PAP leaders as a Chauvinist.
</P>
<P>
The results of the election demonstrated that the voters had
shown their solid support for a multi-racial society with English
as a common working language, Goh said.
</P>
<P>
The PAP only lost two seats in two single-member constituencies
of Potong Pasir and Hougang, which have been the opposition
strongholds since 1991 election.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore People's Party candidate Chiam See Tong was
returned to parliament in the Potong Pasir ward, while Low Thia
Khiang of the Workers' Party retained his seat for the Hougang
constituency.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, however, the PAP recovered two seats it lost
to the opposition Singapore Democratic Party (SDP) in the 1991
general election. Those were the Bukit Gombak and Nee Soon Central
wards.
</P>
<P>
In the battle for the six GRCs, the PAP won a grand slam,
winning all the GRCs, including the hotly-fought Cheng San GRC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
