<HEADLINE> Ghana Records Increased Maize Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Maize production in Ghana has
doubled and prices risen by about 60 percent in the past ten
years.
</P>
<P>
The progress is attributed to the adoption of new planting
techniques by farmers in the west African country, according to
the latest edition of "Spore", a magazine on information for
agricultural development in African and Caribbean countries.
</P>
<P>
Ghana was the first country to receive the help from the
Sasakawa-Global 2,000, an internationally sponsored agricultural
program, followed by Tanzania, Benin, Togo, Nigeria, Ethiopia and
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Uganda, Eritrea, Guinea, Mali and Burkina Faso also
joined in the program.
</P>
<P>
Assisted by the program, Ghanaian farmers have improved their
planting densities and storage facilities, while carrying out
more timely cultivations.
</P>
<P>
"If they had access to fertilizers, their yield could have
been more," the report quoted Chris Dowswell, co-ordinator of the
program, as saying.
</P>
<P>
To improve soil fertility and offset the lack of fertilizers,
the program is developing organic methords such as the use of
green crops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
