<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: S'pore's Ruling PAP Wins All But Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Analyzing the reason behind the PAP victory this time, Goh said
it was mainly because of the "concrete plans we have".
</P>
<P>
As many as 94.61 percent of the 765,332 voters, who were
supposed to vote Thursday, cast their ballots, as voting was
compulsory and secret in Singapore, a tiny island country with a
total of 1,881,011 eligible voters in the election this time.
</P>
<P>
The other 1,115,679 voters did not vote because their
constituencies were already won by the PAP candidates in
walkovers, as the opposition camp did not field any candidates in
those wards.
</P>
<P>
The PAP was thus returned to power on the nomination day on
December 23, 1996, with a total of 47 seats unopposed. The PAP
fielded 83 candidates, the same number as the parliament seats,
while the five opposition parties altogether put up 38 candidates.
There was also one independent candidate, Chia Shi Teck, who lost
his bid in the Chua Chu Kang constituency.
</P>
<P>
Describing the election as "a watershed" event, Goh said the
outcome showed that the Singapore people endorsed what his party
had done in the past five years, and endorsed the party's
Singapore 21 program, a blueprint for Singapore's development in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The results also showed the voters' support for the PAP
approach on concentrating on good government, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said earlier that he would come up with his
new cabinet line-up two weeks after the election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
