<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Capital to Build 160 Primary Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Over 160 primary schools
will be constructed in Dar es Salaam in three years to ease
congestion in the city schools, City Commission Chairman Carles
Keenja said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference to mark the six months since the
commission assumed office, Keenja said the construction will
double the number of primary schools from the present 163.
</P>
<P>
Because of fewer schools in the capital, 200 to 300 pupils
share a classroom in some schools against a national average of
45 pupils each classroom, he said.
</P>
<P>
The city commissioner said that over 1.4 billion Tanzania
Shillings (about 2.3 million U. S. Dollars) will be spent to
construct 12 new primary schools in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On secondary schools, Keenja said each zone in the city will
construct four such schools.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the city commissioner urged city residents,
religious organizations, civic organizations and interested
individuals to contribute to improve the quality of education in
primary and secondary schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
