<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Manufacturing Economy Expands in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National Association
of Purchasing Management (NAPM) said today that economic activity
in U.S. manufacturing sector grew faster than expected in last
December.
</P>
<P>
The NAPM index, a much-watched composite index in the U.S.,
rose by 1.3 percentage points to 54 percent in December from an
unrevised 52.7 percent reading in last November.
</P>
<P>
Most U.S. economists had expected the index to slow to 51.5
percent for the month.
</P>
<P>
The NAPM index is one of the major barometers of the U.S.
economic health during any given month. It is a composite index
based on seasonally adjusted indexes for new orders, production,
vendor deliveries, inventories and employment, with varying
weights applied.
</P>
<P>
A reading above 50 percent generally indicates the U.S.
manufacturing economy is expanding, while a reading below 50
percent suggests the economy is contracting.
</P>
<P>
The rising of the index in December was the eighth time in the
past nine months that the index has indicated U.S. manufacturing
growing with a reading above 50 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
