<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Egyptian Cabinet's First Year Tastes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's current cabinet led by
Prime Minister Kamal Ganzouri could well celebrate the first year
in office over its initial achievement to make the country one of
the "tigers in the Mideast."
</P>
<P>
Luring investments, stepping up privatization and combating
corruption aptly topped the agenda of the 32-man cabinet when it
was elected on January 4, 1996 to replace the nine-year-old
administration of Prime Minister Atef Sidki and "lead the nation
into the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri recruited nine newcomers to deal with finance, economy
and planning in a bid to reverse the much-criticized slow
implementation of reform, started in May 1990.
</P>
<P>
Apparently, the take-over by the "economic group" showed that
economic reform would top the new cabinet's priorities.
</P>
<P>
In his first policy statement, Ganzouri, an architect of the
country's economic reform program, announced that he would focus
on upgrading the living standards of citizens. He promised not to
introduce new taxes or fees or additional burdens.
</P>
<P>
A year later, Egypt reduced the budget deficit by 0.4
percentage point to less than one percent, according to sources
from the Central Bank of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to significant increase of tourism revenues, the
monetary reserves have more than doubled the figure of the
previous year, registering 1.9 billion U.S. dollars by the end of
November.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, with an outstanding ability in foreign trade payment,
has been promoted to the top brackets by international financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
In line with a stable exchange rate, the economy grew by 5
percent in the 1995-96 fiscal year (ending on June 30), compared
with the 4.8 percent average annual economic growth
during 1990-95.
</P>
<P>
As a commendation to Egypt's economic reform, the International
Monetary Fund agreed on October 11 to write off Egypt's 4.2
billion dollars foreign debts under a debt restructuring plan in
1991. The final tranche of the debt accord has been pending since
Egypt and the IMF fell out in 1994, mainly over the government's
exchange rate policy.
</P>
<P>
As much as a seal of international approval, the debt waiver
also heralded in the third phase of the reform program.
</P>
<P>
Just ten months in office, the cabinet has done enough to
convince international investors that Egypt is an attractive
destination in which to place their funds.
</P>
<P>
Foreign portfolio investment has gone up from virtually zero to
380 million dollars from April to September of the year and there
are clear signs of direct investment in new projects.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, applications for 4,996 projects were
approved with a total investment of 7 billion dollars, nearly 9
times the 1994-95 figure of 782.7 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition to that, Egypt also won a string of major
investment deals worth 10 billion dollars at the Cairo Economic
Conference held on November 12-14. Thus Egypt succeeded in
putting the country on international investors' map.
</P>
<P>
Under the Egyptian privatization program, a string of
regulations were introduced to protect the rights of the state
while allowing people to buy shares of state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
The private sector, which is allowed to invest in services,
reportedly contributes more than 80 percent of the investment.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to reverse the perennial trade imbalance, the
cabinet has put up various incentives and facilities to encourage
export, including the treatment of export-oriented output on a par
with the production of the free zones, the elimination of all fees
on export inspection and the reduction of freight cost at ports.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to clean the government's image, Ganzouri vowed there
would be no cover-up for corruption, nor protection for any
official who tampers with state funds.
</P>
<P>
A series of crackdowns on economic crimes followed, crowned by
the arrest of Abdel-Wahab Habbaq, chairman of the Holding Company
for Engineering Industries, who allegedly gained as much as 30
million dollars in illicit commissions which he safely deposited
in foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead, Ganzouri said the investment target is 60
billion pounds (18 billion dollars) in 1996-97, the first year of
the fourth five-year plan. He also predicated an economic growth
of 6.2 percent and annual creation of 400,000 jobs in the next
two years.
</P>
<P>
To give privatization a push, the cabinet decided last
February to sell off 61 companies and 36 hotels owned by the
public sector by the end of June 1998, generating 4 billion to 5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
A new canal project, the so-called "project of the 21 century,"
will be launched soon in the country. By cultivating at least
500,000 feddans (210,000 hectares) in the Western Desert, the
project will increase the arable land by 16 percent in its first
stage and effectively change the country's demographic map.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Hotel Industry Gains Record Profits in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The hotel industry in the
United States gained record profits in 1996, the fourth
consecutive year-- a long stretch for a business known for severe
boom-and-bust cycles, the New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The industry fetched 11.5 billion U.S. dollars last year, a far
cry from the last recession, when the industry, reeling from the
effects of a huge building spree, lost 5.7 billion U.S. dollars in
1991 alone.
</P>
<P>
Now hotels look for 5th year of growing profitability. The
outlook for 1997 is favorable. Coopers &AMP; Lybrand, the accounting
and consulting firm, forecasts a record 11.9 billion U.S. dollars
in industry profits. The firm predicts a slightly decrease in
occupancy, down from last year's estimated rate of 66 per cent,
which is about average for the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
However, economists noted that the hotel industry, despite
attempts to manage its assets more efficiently, cannot shake off
the pattern of overbuilding and retrenchment that makes it
particularly vulnerable to to swings in business activities.
</P>
<P>
Over the last 25 years, according to a report issued last year
by Salomon Brothers Company, the hotel industry has been basically
sticking to the pattern like this: During good times, high demand
brings money pouring into the industry, which recycles it to
finance new hotel rooms. The good times end when recession dries
up demand or overbuilding runs ahead of growth and the resulting
glut strangles profitability.
</P>
<P>
In a fresh attempt to shake off the pattern, the industry has
adopted a new strategy whose emphasis is on efficiency and holding
down labor costs. Most new hotels are far smaller, offer a
continental breakfast or a small food court in place of a
restaurant, and require less labor than older hotels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
