<HEADLINE> Russia to Expand Ties With Asia in 1997: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia will expand its ties with
countries in the Asia-Pacific region this year, Deputy Foreign
Minister Grigory Karasin said today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Interfax News Agency, Karasin, who is
in charge of Asian-Pacific affairs, outlined plans for Russia's
high-ranking contacts with China, India and Japan in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin will visit China
this year, as part of an Asia tour which will take him to two or
three other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The planned visit by Chinese President Jiang Zemin to Moscow in
the spring of 1997 will be a very important event, Karasin said.
</P>
<P>
Indian Foreign Minister Inder Kumar Gujral will visit Russia
later this month, laying the groundwork for Prime Minister Deve
Gowda's visit to Moscow in the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Russian-Japanese Inter-governmental Commission on Economic
Cooperation will hold a meeting in Tokyo in late February or early
March. A task force meeting to draft a peace treaty between the two
countries will be held in Moscow later this year. 
</P>
