<HEADLINE> Construction of Guangzhou Subway Going on Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Smooth construction will
enable the first subway in Guangzhou, south China's largest
metropolis, to open to traffic in June.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last November, construction on 75 percent of the
main structure, nine tunnels, and ten stations had been completed.
</P>
<P>
The 5.3-kilometer-long section between Xilang and Huangsha,
scheduled to open to traffic on June 28 this year, has finished
track laying.
</P>
<P>
The subway, which will be heavily-equipped with foreign-made
facilities, got its first batch of Germany imports in last August,
followed by British and Japanese equipment. These will ensure the
subway to meet international advanced standards of the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that in April the 20 German-made trains will
arrive in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
The No.one line is designed to handle 55,800 passengers per
hour. By 2000, the subway will accommodate ten to 15 percent of
the passenger flow of Guangzhou, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
