<HEADLINE> Tigers Rally to Down Lions at Chinese Pro Basketball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Jilin Tigers came from a
halftime deficit to beat Beijing Lions 116-99 Friday, sharing the
top place with 14 wins and four losses at the Chinese Men's
Basketball Professional League.
</P>
<P>
The Tigers, led by American David Vanterpool's 33 points and
seven rebounds, trailed by three points at 52-55 in the first half
and jumped to lead with a 8-0 run in the beginning of the third
period.
</P>
<P>
The Lions, which played without their 2.14-meter starting
center Maurie Barnett, whose brother was shot dead in America on
New Year's Eve, closed the score to 72-75 with Sun Fengwu's layup
with five minutes to go in the third period.
</P>
<P>
"We lost two players on the court tonight, Barnett and Cai
Shenghe. And we were outrebounded 33-45 by our opponents. Our
offensive was also bad," said Sun Fengwu, who scored 25 points to
lead the Lions.
</P>
<P>
Barnett, who always dominated the middle in the league, has
gone to the United States and will be back on January 12th, said
the Lions' American coach Joe Weakley.
</P>
<P>
"They looked a little bit tired," said Li Xuefeng, coach of
Jilin, whose American coach Don Sellers was sacked last week for
his "repeated flagrant violations of CNBA rules" by the Spectrum.
</P>
<P>
"If Barnett were in the action tonight, it would have been
another result. It would be hard to say who were winners," Li
Xuefeng added.
</P>
<P>
Sun Jun added 30 points and grabbed 10 rebounds for Jilin.
</P>
<P>
In the other games Friday, the Guangzhou Rams whitewashed the
Tianjin Breakers 121-86, the Shanghai Nanyang won over the Hubei
Caranes 113-101 and the Henan Wildcats downed the Fujian Storm
115-106. 
</P>
</TEXT>
