<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People Of Shanghai Now Collecting Cards, Not Just Using Them </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The residents of Shanghai now
have something else to collect -- magnetic cards of various kinds,
which they are holding on to instead of putting them to practical
use.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China's largest city has issued many types of
magnetic cards: for phones, taxis, ferries, subways, and cinemas,
which have in turn caught the attention of local stamp collectors,
due to the simple fact that the cards are increasing in value much
faster than stamps are.
</P>
<P>
The collecting craze is unfortunately ignoring the original
purpose of the cards, which was to speed up payment or movement of
traffic.
</P>
<P>
Local experts advise collectors not to forget the practical
purpose of the cards, and suggest that the issuers learn from the
manufacturers of stamps how to separate the practical use cards
from those for collection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Army, U.S. Agency to Renovate Highway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian army will
cooperate with a U.S. agency to rebuild Highway 10, a major road
linking the provincial capital of Battambang with Pailin, a former
Khmer Rouge stronghold which came under government control last
August, a senior army official said today.
</P>
<P>
Highway 10 has been seriously damaged by logging trucks
transporting logs from the thick forests in the area.
</P>
<P>
The army will first clear mines along a 20-kilometer section of
the highway near Pailin, in preparation for the project supported
by the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID),
Brigadier General Lay Bun Song, Director of the Foreign Relations
Department of the Defense Ministry, said.
</P>
<P>
Mine-clearance operations will start soon as other sections of
the road have been largely cleared of mines.
</P>
<P>
The army's Engineering Department will provide labor and
machinery for the project which will begin as soon as the mine
clearing is finished, Lay said.
</P>
<P>
He did not say how much money USAID planned to put into the
project, saying the Defense Ministry has sent a draft plan to the
U.S. embassy in Phnom Penh and is waiting for a reply.
</P>
<P>
General Ly Seng Hong, Deputy Chief of Staff in charge of
military development, confirmed today that mine-clearing troops
were deployed in the relevant areas two weeks ago and work should
be finished by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Raksmei Kampuchea today quoted General Kwan
Siem, Commander of the Engineering Troops, as saying that the
20-kilometer section from Sour Sadey village to Pailin is
estimated to have 20 to 30 mines per hectare.
</P>
<P>
A USAID official who asked for anonymity said his agency will
start rebuilding 1,200 kilometers of highways in the eastern
provinces of Battambang, Siem Reap and Banteay Meanchey in
October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
