<HEADLINE> France Condemns Bomb Attack on Bus in Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 3 (Xinhua) -- France today condemned the bomb
attack Tuesday on a passenger bus in the Syrian capital of
Damascus, in which a dozen people were reportedly killed.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt described
the attack as "cowardly" and said that one should "rapidly get
right to the bottom" of the attack.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the attack showed that all countries in the
world are "exposed to the scourge of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
The French government learned with shock about the cowardly
attack committed on December 31, and has sent its condolences to
the Syrian government, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
France "condemns any act of violence no matter what its origin
is or who its producers are. This act confirms that a same
solidarity should unite all the people in the fight against blind
violence and for the search of peace," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Syria has accused the Israeli intelligence service Mossad of
having masterminded the attack. Israel denied the charge as "a big
lie."
</P>
<P>
A bombing attack on a Paris underground train on December 3,
1996, killed four people and wounded about 90. 
</P>
</TEXT>
