<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Fighters Bomb PKK Camps in Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish F-4 fighters bombarded
this morning the camps of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK) based in northern Iraq, the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the fighters, which took off from the air
base in Diyarbakir, center of southeastern Turkey, bombarded and
destroyed many camps in the Sinath region where PKK military
bases are established inside northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the Turkish security forces staged
stronger air raids against the PKK militants who tried to flee
from Sindi Throat in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A total of 101 PKK rebels have been killed in Turkey's
cross-border operations in northern Iraq for the past four days,
the agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish village guards also participated in the cross-border
operations launched by the Turkish government troops.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi official newspaper al-Thawra, organ of the ruling Baath
party, Thursday condemned Turkey for sending troops into northern
Iraq in pursuit of the PKK militants, saying: "Such an operation
is rejected."
</P>
<P>
The PKK uses bases in northern Iraq outside Baghdad's control
as part of its guerrilla war for self-rule in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government troops have crossed into northern Iraq
several times in large numbers in a bid to wipe out the PKK
rebels, who intermittently launch cross-border attacks against
Turkish military and civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government has made protests against the Turkish
cross-border operations before and accused Turkey of violating
its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Over 21,000 people including PKK rebels, civilians and
government troops have been killed in conflicts since August
1984 when the illegal organization started the guerrilla
war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
