<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Economy Set to Grow 5 Pct in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Ireland's
economic boom is set to continue this year with real GNP growth of
5 percent, according to a report of Ireland's independent economic
institute.
</P>
<P>
The Quarterly Economic Review from the Economic and Social
Research Institute estimated that real GNP growth in 1996 was
around 5.75 percent, after growth in excess of 7 percent for 1995
and 1994.
</P>
<P>
The review predicted that a deceleration of growth in demestic
demand in 1997 will be offset by rapid expansion in export
volumes.
</P>
<P>
Inflation, which was running at 1.6 percent in 1996, should
stay under control at around 2 percent in 1997, said the review.
</P>
<P>
It also said that although no estimate of economic progress can
be definitive, "the trends in the various major elements fit
together in a generally coherent manner."
</P>
<P>
Economic experts say that Ireland's healthy economic
performance is attributed to, among other matters, direct foreign
investment in fast-growing industries and the availability of a
qualified labor force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
