<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Quality Improvement Outline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The State Council, China's
highest governing body, has developed a "Quality Improvement
Outline" to promote quality in industrial products, engineering
projects, and services in the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
It said that at present, product quality, and that of projects
and services is not keeping pace with improvements in people's
standard of living and social development, and is lagging far
behind respective sectors in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
It also said that a number of internationally-competitive
industries and giant corporations need to be developed by the year
2000, and by the year 2010 the overall quality of leading
industries should be able to compete in the international economy.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, more than 75 percent of major industrial products are
expected to comply with advanced international standards and, by
2010 the figure will go up to 85 percent, and after-sale service
will improved accordingly.
</P>
<P>
The outline provided specific goals for raw materials, key
machinery and electronic parts, large-scale equipment, and
consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
In regard to engineering projects, 90 percent will have to
qualify in first-round quality checks by the year 2000, and by
2010, that rate will have to go up to 96.
</P>
<P>
To improve service, the outline noted, the public will need a
better understanding of existing laws and regulations on improving
quality, and local governments and departments should improve
management and supervision, as well as law-enforcement in the area
of quality control.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the country will need enact more laws and
regulations to cover major trades, while urging various businesses
and institutions to improve their quality through more scientific
management techniques, technical improvements, and a system of
awards, as well as in other ways, the outline said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
