<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Calls for Revitalizing State-Owned Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- In a recent tour of China's
largest city, Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua stressed the importance of
revitalizing large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises there.
</P>
<P>
This is tied to the country's economic growth and social
stability and the process of building a socialist market economy,
Zou said during the inspection tour.
</P>
<P>
Zou, who is a member of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) Central Committee, pointed to the city's
achievements over the past year, saying that "I witness new and
great changes in Shanghai every year I go there."
</P>
<P>
Zou listened to reports by Huang Ju, secretary of the CPC
Shanghai Municipal Committee, and Shanghai Mayor Xu Kuangdi, and
visited some leading companies.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has made great achievements in the dealing with the
state-owned enterprises and has gotten a certain amount of
experience, Zou said, saying that he hopes the city will play a
major role in the country in these reforms.
</P>
<P>
He also said that all of society should be mobilized to help
unemployed workers, who are in difficulties and should be given
new work opportunities.  
</P>
