<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Gives First Death Penalties for 1994 Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 3 (Xinhua) -- A male nurse and a former official
were condemned to death today by a Rwandan court for participating
in the 1994 ethnic genocide against the minority Tutsis and
moderate Hutus, the local press reported.
</P>
<P>
The trial, the first of its kind by a court of Rwanda
concerning the massacres of at least 500,000 people, was held
on December 27, 1996. Some 90,000 Hutus in jail awaiting trial
for their parts in the genocide.
</P>
<P>
The defendants, Deogratias Bizimana and Egide Gatanazi did not
have defense attorneys and pleaded not guilty in a trial which
lasted only a few hours in a court in Kibungo, southeast Rwanda,
Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted Radio Rwanda as saying that the two men have two
weeks to appeal against the sentence in a higher court.
</P>
<P>
Bizimana, accused of joining massacres and leading "bands of
killers," said during the trial that he was forced to admit his
crimes after being tortured.
</P>
<P>
Gatanazi, accused of rape and looting, denied the charges and
accused the government of "conspiracy" against him, although his
own sister was among the witnesses who testified against him.
</P>
<P>
The two men were the first to be tried for the genocide in
Rwanda from April to July 1994, triggered by the death of Rwandan
President Juvenal Habyramana and his Burundian counterpart
President Cyprian Ntaryamira in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
The bloody civil war which followed led to the massacre of
at least 500,000 minority Tutsis and moderate Hutus by Hutu
troops, militia and mobs.
</P>
<P>
The genocide ended when the Tutsi-dominated rebel Rwanda
Patriotic Front defeated the old Hutu government and took power,
sending millions of Hutu refugees fleeing into neighboring
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
