<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cold Weather Paralyzes French Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Freezing weather from Siberia
almost paralyzed traffic in central and southern France Thursday
night and Friday morning, an Agence France-Presse (AFP) report
said today.
</P>
<P>
Snowfalls and frost left about 10,000 train passengers stranded
Thursday night in Lyon, the central region of Bourgogne and the
southern departments of Bouches-du-Rhone and Vaucluse.
</P>
<P>
Early Friday morning, the French state railway company SNCF
started evacuating passengers from trains stuck between Lyon and
the southeastern city of Valence via an emergency shuttle train.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two of some eight high-speed TGV trains which were
immobilized in Lyon on Thursday were still in the station this
morning, and the SNCF canceled Friday's train schedules down the
Rhone Valley.
</P>
<P>
Icy rain and snow also made driving treacherous on the highways
in several regions, including Bretagne, Auvergne, Rhone-Alpes and
Provence.
</P>
<P>
The Lyon to Marseille section of the main north-south highway
was closed Thursday after one man was killed and 16 others injured
in 18 traffic accidents Wednesday night alone.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,000 to 5,000 cars were stranded on the roads of the
department of Rhone Thursday night, and some drivers had to take
shelter in emergency rescue centers.
</P>
<P>
Officials from a Lyon-based emergency team said that conditions
on the roads around the city were improving slowly as the snow
stopped and snow-clearing work got underway.
</P>
<P>
The extreme cold weather, which started on Christmas eve, has
already claimed 22 deaths in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
