<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Regularizes Construction Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- A management center was set up
in Beijing today to regularize the market of construction
businesses in the Chinese Capital.
</P>
<P>
Any construction project exceeding 500,000 yuan (over 60,000
U.S. dollars) in cost will have to submit a proposal to the
management center for public bidding. This also covers
construction projects with a floor space of more than 2,000 square
meters each.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zongli, director of the Beijing Municipal Construction
Committee, said that the center is an essential regulatory move by
the municipal government, and that it will help provide a more
open environment for competition in Beijing's construction market.
</P>
<P>
The center will help units in charge of construction projectors
with application, bidding, construction management, contracts, and
building quality, making the construction market better for buyers
and sellers.
</P>
<P>
Construction work in Beijing has made great progress in the
past decade, with more than 100 million square meters of housing
having been built and many national or municipal key projects
completed.
</P>
<P>
The number of units involved in construction in Beijing has
grown to over 2,400 with nearly one million employees from some 70
with about 200,000 employees in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Some problems occurred with all this prosperity, Wang said,
noting that the lack of bidding and filling in of application
papers, and the lack of supervision over quality have caused
damage to state and individual property, in turn affecting the
quality and efficiency of the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
