<HEADLINE> S. African Space Fans Can Talk to U.S. Astronaut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Six South African space
zealots will have a chance to chatter with the famous American
astronaut, John Blaha, on the Russian Space Station MIR as it is
due to be over South Africa on the coming Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here today by Telecommunication (Telkom)
Manager Hans Van de Groenendaal, adding that the lucky birds, who
are yet to be selected among the kids, will be connected to MIR
via Telkom lines from an amateur radio station in Durban.
</P>
<P>
"It is a a great opportunity for kids to ask Blaha questions
on space travel and for their parents and the public to
participate in the venture by tuning in," said Groenendaal.
</P>
<P>
Those who want to enter must provide a 100-word brief
discussion on why space exploration is important for mankind and
offer two questions.
</P>
<P>
"So far we have got 15 applicants, but there is still time for
interested youngsters to enter," he said, adding that the final
decision on the participants will be made by 10 a.m. on the
coming Saturday.
</P>
<P>
An agreement signed between Washington and Pretoria two years
ago has made it possible for South Africans to speak to
astronauts almost once every 18 months, said Groenendaal. 
</P>
