<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cure for Hangovers Still a Long Way Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- A cure for hangovers is probably
unattainable because the throbbing headache, tremors and sense of
anxiety are triggered by a cocktail of chemicals in alcoholic
drinks rather than by the alcohol itself, doctors said today in
The British Medical Journal.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ian Calder of the National Hospital for Neurology and
Neurosurgery, London, said that congeners -- complex organic
molecules such as methanol and acetones in alcoholic drinks -- are
more to blame than alcohol for the morning-after symptoms of a
heavy drinking session.
</P>
<P>
He said this explains why over-indulgence in drinks high in
congeners, such as brandy or red wine, tends to cause worse
hangovers than vodka or pure ethanol which are low in congeners.
</P>
<P>
The hangover "league table" runs from brandy and red wine at
the top, through rum, whisky, white wine and gin, to vodka and
pure alcohol at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Calder, says levels of alcohol in the blood do not relate
to the severity of a hangover. Hangovers are at their worst when
almost all alcohol has cleared from the blood.
</P>
<P>
But methanol and the chemicals into which it breaks down are
still present in the blood and research has suggested they may
relate to the severity of the hangover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
