<HEADLINE> Indonesia Determined to Reduce Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
determined to reduce the population growth rate by 0.15 percent to
1.51 percent this year from 1.66 percent in 1996, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
"To achieve that goal, efforts will be made through the
'reproduction movement to achieve a prosperous family' which is an
extension of the family planning program," said State Minister for
Population Affairs Haryono Suyono at a workshop on research and
the development of a prosperous family here today.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the government would continue to develop
the self-supporting family planning movement, the prosperous and
healthy mother movement and the other already existing movements.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia had a population of 199.7 million at the end of 1996,
the world's fourth most populous country after China, India and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Haryono said that Indonesia had at present 11.5
million families or 27.2 million people who were still living
below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Haryono, who is also chief of the National Family Planning
Coordinating Board, said the board will do its utmost to reduce
the number of poor people to about 12 million by the end of the
Sixth Five-year Development Plan (1994-99).
</P>
<P>
The board will also further raise the welfare of the poor by
enhancing their awareness to save, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
