<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Closes Detention Center for Vietnamese Migrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Whitehead Detention Center
for Vietnamese Migrants (VMs) was closed here today as the VM
population in Hong Kong dropped to a record low of 6,300 at the
end of 1996, according to an official release.
</P>
<P>
More than 63,000 VMs had been repatriated under the voluntary
and orderly repatriation programs since 1989, said Acting Refugee
Coordinator Sally Wong.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 alone, 15,100 VMs were repatriated thanks to
accelerated pace, setting the highest annual repatriation record,
she added. The declining VM size had led to the closure of Tai A
Chau Detention Center in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
The transfer operation today at Whitehead proceeded smoothly,
Wong said. The center's main camp was closed, with only minor
units left open for providing temporary facilities for some VMs
immediately prior to their repatriation.
</P>
<P>
She described Whitehead's closure as "a watershed in the whole
VM saga, signaling the beginning of the end of the problem."
</P>
<P>
The center was first opened in January 1989 when the VM
population in Hong Kong stood at about 11,000. When the VM
population reached its height of nearly 60,000 in October 1991,
the center provided accommodation for about 25,000.
</P>
<P>
"The government is firmly committed to resolving the problem of
the remaining VMs in Hong Kong as soon as possible," Wong said.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the remaining VMs are now accommodated in High
Island Detention Center.
</P>
<P>
"Should the current rate of repatriation continue, it should be
possible to close all VM camps by the middle of this year," Wong
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
