<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Majority of China's College Students Paying Tuition Themselves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese university students can
no longer look to the state for funding their education, and now
face the hard truth of paying for tuition by themselves.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission (SEC) said today that more than
64 percent of China's colleges and universities have started to
ask the students to pay tuition fees.
</P>
<P>
This practice is considered as part of China's reform on the
educational system of the institutes of higher learning for last
year. One SEC official says that about 966,000 freshmen recruited
by some 1,000 universities last year, among them 661 universities
began the practice.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Education Law, the SEC and the State
Statistics Bureau have supervised national educational input for
three years running. SEC has also adopted a provisional regulation
on tuition charging. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
