<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Study May Lead To Vaccination Against Asthma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have come up with
evidence that childhood chest infections protect children against
asthma.
</P>
<P>
Their research suggests it may be possible to vaccinate against
asthma and other allergies using harmless bacteria related to
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
A study published in the journal Science today has linked the
decline in tuberculosis to the rise of an immune response that
underlies extreme sensitivity to dust, pollen and other allergens.
</P>
<P>
The findings show that it should be possible to produce
vaccines to overcome the current asthma epidemic in the UK and to
prevent other allergic responses.
</P>
<P>
There has been a steady rise in asthma among people in
developed countries this century. In Britain, there has been a 50
percent increase in childhood cases in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The study, by Dr. Julian Hopkin, of the Churchill Hospital,
Oxford, and colleagues in Japan, found that Japanese children with
a strong immune response to tuberculosis were relatively
insensitive to allergens such as dust mites and pollen, and thus
less prone to asthma.
</P>
<P>
"These experiments point to the possibility that immunization
with harmless bacteria, related to tuberculosis, might be helpful
in preventing and treating allergy," said Dr Hopkin. "Further
studies to test this idea are planned." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
