<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chain-store Competition Internationalized in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- As foreign chain stores are
creating a stronger presence in Shanghai, the competition for the
market share in the city is taking on a more international flavor.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, multinational giants such as Yaohan
of Japan, Carrefour of France, Royal Ahold of Holland, and Chia
Tai of Thailand have invested in chain stores in Shanghai, which
are considered the most promising form of commerce in the 1990s in
China's largest city.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures show that the foreign companies have already
opened over 40 chain stores in Shanghai, which have been
successful and have a competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
The chain stores under France's Carrefour, for example, are
able to sell commodities for 10-20 percent less than the market
price, and everyday promotional sales of 30 types of goods are
priced 30 percent lower than many of the store's counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The foreign investment is still expanding: Ahold plans to
transform 15 local department stores into chain stores within the
next year, and Youhan will increase the number of its chain stores
from 20 to 175 by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
And in a similar show of spirit, local businesses have formed
28 chain store companies to run some 1,000 stores.
</P>
<P>
However, when compared with their counterparts, the local
companies still seem to lack muscle, market analysts pointed out.
</P>
<P>
One problem is their inadequate business scale, which prevents
them from setting up distribution centers that are crucial for
reducing costs.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the shortfalls, many local companies are considering
pooling their resources by merging and other forms of asset
reorganization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
