<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM Urges Scientists to Overcome West's Technology Denial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Deve Gowda
today urged Indian scientists to hit back at attempts of advanced
countries to deny frontier technologies to India.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the 84th Indian Science Congress at the Delhi
University here, Gowda said that technology denials are widening
the gap between developing and developed nations and Indian
scientists should find suitable and effective alternatives to
tackle the barriers being created by the West.
</P>
<P>
The country should also be careful that obsolete and
environmentally harmful technologies that are being phased out
elsewhere are not passed on to developing countries in the name of
technology transfer, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
To prevent this, there is a need for a technology information
system that can help policy-makers adapt the right technologies
for national use, he said.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet the global challenges in the frontier areas of
technology, scientists should also ensure that these are made
available to users at affordable prices, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
