<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Inundate 3,000 Houses in C. Java, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Floods triggered by three days
of downpour hit a number of districts in the northern coast of
Central Java, Indonesia, inundating more than 3,000 houses and
forcing hundreds of people to evacuate their homes, Antara News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Worst hit was Pekalongan municipality where floods submerged
2,618 houses in water as high as 1.25 meters, forcing 261 people
to move to safer grounds, a source at the Pekalongan Natural
Disaster Control Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities have provided the flood victims with
rice, instant noodles and medicine to help ease their burden, said
the source.
</P>
<P>
The incessant rains in the past three days have also caused
landslides in Kayupuring village, Pekalongan district, cutting off
land communications between the subdistricts of Petungkriyono and
Doro.
</P>
<P>
The rains also caused the Winong river in Sragi subdistrict,
Pekalongan district, to overflow, inundating 19 hectares of small
sugarcane plantation, 30 hectares of ricefield and tens of houses,
said the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
