<HEADLINE> Curfew Enforced in Indonesia's Riot Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- A curfew was imposed on Thursday
in Sanggau Ledo village of Sambas district of Indonesia's West
Kalimantan province, following a youth rampage last Sunday, Antara
News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Residents of Sanggau Ledo are requested to stay inside their
homes from 9:00 p.m. to 4:00 a.m., Sambas district head Tarya
Arbianto was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rampage broke out in Sanggau Ledo, more than 800 kilometers
north of Jakarta, because of misunderstanding between youth
groups, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of residents in Sanggau Ledo left their homes after a
mob burned and looted scores of homes and stores, the report said.
</P>
<P>
West Kalimantan military chief Maj. Gen. Namuri Anum said that
six persons were held on suspicion of inciting the riot that led
to the rampage.
</P>
<P>
He said the unrest was sparked by a dispute during a pop music
concert in Sanggau Ledo on Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, The Jakarta Post newspaper said that the riot had
claimed five lives and inflicted injuries on nine others.
</P>
