<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Netanyahu's Coalition Suffers Internal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu is facing increasing rebellion among his
ministers over reaching an agreement with Palestinians on Israeli
troop redeployment in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Until now, seven out of 18 ministers within the Likud-led
coalition have already declared unequivocally that they would
not support the Hebron deal, while several others are still
wavering.
</P>
<P>
The seven ministers include Infrastructure Minister Ariel
Sharon, Ze'ev Beigin and Communications Minister Limor Livnat of
the Likud, Education Minister Zvulun Hammer and Transportation
Minister Yithzak Levy of the National Religious Party,
Agriculture Minister Rafael Eitan of the Tsomet and Yuli
Edelstein of the Yisrael Ba'aliya.
</P>
<P>
In a sign of worsening problem, Likud's Justice Minister
Tzahi Hanegbi declared Thursday that he might vote against the
Hebron deal if it was true that Israel had abandoned its
insistence on the Palestinian Authority's (PA) extradition of
suspected Palestinian terrorists.
</P>
<P>
The ministers have been grumbling about their exclusion from
the Hebron talks despite Netanyahu's promise that he would
bring the deal to the cabinet for approval after its
signing.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has been personally leading a three-man committee,
which also includes Foreign Minister David Levy and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, to supervise the Hebron negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The rebellious ministers also claimed that the Hebron deal
was tantamount to abandoning the 450 Jewish settlers living
among 120,000 Palestinians in Hebron, where the Jewish holy
shrine the Tomb of Patriarchs is located. At least, they
demanded major revisions to the original agreement on Hebron
redeployment, which was reached by the previous Labor government
with the PA.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has been trying but failed to achieve major
revisions to the original Hebron agreement after over three
months of marathon talks. The only compromises that he got
from the PA is to erect a buffer zone and to downgrade the
arms of the Palestinian police.
</P>
<P>
Rafael Eitan, who is Netanyahu's close election partner,
denounced the Hebron deal for opening the door for increasing
U.S. and European pressure to force Israel to make more
territorial concessions.
</P>
<P>
"Hebron is the gate way through which the Arabs will
march to destroy the entire Zionist entity," the right-wing
former Chief of Staff claimed in a letter to Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Within Netanyahu's own Likud party, the anti-agreement
sentiment seemed decidedly as shown at the Likud political bureau
meeting held Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Netanyahu's Coalition Suffers Internal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sharon, the hardline former Defense Minister, complained about
the monoply of the negotiations by Netanyahu. "I had a better plan
which could have minimized the dangers. It's too bad no one saw
fit to talk to me and hear me out," he told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Beigin, another tough opponent of Hebron pullout, asserted
that the Hebron agreement will lead to a total pullback from all
the territories. "Hebron is the last dam, when it bursts, the
deluge will come," he said.
</P>
<P>
Opponents to such a Hebron deal already gave a warning to
Netanyahu during the Tuesday's vote in the Knesset (Parliament) on
the no-confidence motion against the government over the Hebron
talks, which was tabled by the extremist right-wing opposition
party Moledet.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu mainly relied on major opposition parties' indirect
support to avert a power crisis. The result of the vote is 47
against, two in favor and 34 abstentions. A large number of
coalition lawmakers refrained from voting for the government,
which could otherwise be toppled if the Labor, Meretz and Arab
lawmakers voted against.
</P>
<P>
In light of the strong opposition within the coalition
government, analysts said that the Hebron deal could be
torpedoed when it is brought to the cabinet for approval.
</P>
<P>
Noticeably, the beset Netanyahu held a meeting Thursday
with the opposition Labor leader and former premier Shimon
Peres. Tough no detail was disclosed about the meeting, some
observers guessed that Netanyahu is apparently considering the
option of forming a national unity government with the Labor.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial, the Hebrew daily Hatzofeh believed the
Natanyahu-Peres meeting was of "special significance" for forming
a unity government in light of Netanyahu's displeasure over
dissent within the coalition.
</P>
<P>
The formation of a unity government would the easiest way to
pull Netanyhau out of the current political quagmire, but it will
be impossible before he dramatically changes the Likud's hardline
policies that differ distinctively from those of the
Labor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
