<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ammunition Arrival Causes Tension in Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The arrival of more than 70
tons of ammunition and weapons at north Mogadishu controlled by
warlord Ali Mahdi Mohamed, has brought about tension once again
in the war-torn capital city here.
</P>
<P>
The munitions were off loaded from seven lorries in the day
time Wednesday at a store near the busy junction of Sana before
hundreds of ordinary people here.
</P>
<P>
The witnesses said the munitions included 30 tons of rounds
for the assault rifles, 10 tons of the anti-tank b-10 rounds, 10
tons of mortar rounds and a truck of assault rifles of AK-47.
</P>
<P>
It was believed there were 20 tons of anti-aircraft missiles
unloaded at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Mohamed Aidid, another faction's leader, has accused
Ethiopia of offering weapons to his rival Ali Mahdi, his
spokesman Mohamed Qanyare Afrah said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia had provided 84 tons of arms and ammunition to
Ali Mhadi, said Afrah.
</P>
<P>
The weapons reached Mogadishu from the Ethiopian military base
of Shilabo, near te Somali border, and via the Hiran region of
central Somalia, Afrah quoted his faction's intelligence sources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Afrah charged that Ethiopia has violated the UN resolution
733, issued in January 1992 to impose arms embargo on Somalia.
</P>
<P>
However, Hussein Sheikh Ahmed Kadare, the press secretary of
Ali Mahdi Mohamed, denied the offer of weapons by Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
He described Afrah's accusation as baseless, saying Somali
merchants were also involved in the arms trafficking and that
there is no bans on his faction to buy arms from merchants.
</P>
<P>
People fear that the arrival of this large amount of
ammunition in Mogadishu would reignite the eased hostility in
Mogadishu since the recent fighting in Mogadishu had died down
after the warring factions had ran out of ammunition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
