<HEADLINE> Pak PM Calls for Resolution of Indo-Pak Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani caretaker Prime
Minister Malik Miraj Khalid today called for fair and just
resolution of basic differences between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Khalid made the appeal at the Council Session of the Afro-Asian
People's Solidarity Organization in Karachi, the southern port
city of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said that one billion people of this region will continue to
live without peace unless basic differences between India and
Pakistan are resolved fairly and justly.
</P>
<P>
He said that the South Asian Association of Regional
Cooperation which came into existence because of the spade work
provided by Afro-Asian People's Solidarity Organization, has
played a role to bring peace in the region where people were
victims of basic conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The caretaker prime minister said that despite the fact that
Pakistan has attained independence and is a free country today,
"we are still victims of various prejudices."
</P>
<P>
"Under this faith we should have good wishes for entire
humanity and in keeping with this faith the Organization of
Afro-Asian Solidarity is the protagonist of the cause of humanity,
having no belief in the caste, color or creed," Khalid said.
</P>
<P>
The Afro-Asian Solidarity Organization is the best forum for
elaboration of the high principles of humanity, respect to
humanity and justice, Khalid added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
