<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Women Become Literate in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 3 (Xinhua) -- With the deepening of the
poverty relief program, more than one million young women in
landlocked Gansu Province have become literate.
</P>
<P>
Located in northwest China, Gansu is a comparatively backward
province that constantly faces a shortage of funds for economic
and cultural development.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1980s, the province was reported to have more than
four million women who were illiterate.
</P>
<P>
Since 1986, Gansu has carried out two anti-illiteracy campaigns
and opened 60,000 educational training classes.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 200,000 women were encouraged to attend training
schools, and among them, 120,000 have received education.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that another 25 special classes have opened for
girl drop-outs in 15 poverty-stricken counties where ethnic groups
live in compact communities.
</P>
<P>
The enrollment rate of school-age girls has reportedly reached
90 percent, and nearly 7,000 poor girls received aid from local
authorities and returned to their classrooms, according to
statistics.
</P>
<P>
The training classes also teach practical skills to help local
women overcome poverty. Since 1986, four million women have taken
the courses, and 70 percent of them have grasp one or more
practical skills. In 1996, 500,000 women benefitted from the
courses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Starts Repatriation of Illegal Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has started
repatriation of illegal immigrants with more than 1,200
Indonesians setting sail for home today, the Malaysian national
news agency Bernama reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesians, mostly from the Indonesian island of Java,
left Malaysia's Pasir Gudang port in Johore Bahru aboard an
Indonesian naval ship under the supervision of Indonesian military
personnel and the Malaysian Police Field Force.
</P>
<P>
These immigrants had been brought to the port by police trucks
from seven camps in various parts of Malaysia, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the transport costs were shared by the
governments of Indonesia and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
This is Malaysia's first repatriation of illegal immigrants
since a six-month amnesty expired on December 31 last year. Some
300,000 illegal immigrants had registered themselves with the
authorities in the past six months.
</P>
<P>
According to Indonesian Ambassador to Malaysia Mohd Jacob
Dasto, the two countries will study the effectiveness of
repatriation via naval vessels and would continue the program if
it is found to be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Home Ministry Secretary General Samsudin Osman said
that his government hopes more countries whose nationals entered
Malaysia illegally would take them back to ensure their safe
return and save transport costs for Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He said some 12,000 illegal immigrants were still staying at
eight detention depots in the country, mostly from Indonesia,
Bangladesh, Myanmar and India.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
