<HEADLINE> Crime Rate Declines in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The rate of violent crimes
sharply declined in Uganda in 1996, the "Monitor" newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
John Cossy Odomel, the inspector general of police, was quoted
as saying that crimes fell because of the improved mobility and
communications of the police in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The foot patrols have enforced the police to be at the spot
of every incident early enough," he said when addressing a
year-end police party on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He also praised Kampala police for their successful raids on
gangs once terrorizing the capital city.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the fighting with rampant corruption will be at
high agenda of the police's five-year development plan, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Odomel failed to give the exact figure of the crime
rate. 
