<HEADLINE> Arafat Hardens Position on Hebron Deal: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Authority (PA)
President Yasser Arafat has refused to meet Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu as he hardens position on reaching the Hebron
agreement, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Arafat Thursday rejected U.S. Special Envoy Dennis Ross'
proposal to hold a summit with Netanyahu to initial the Hebron
deal. Israeli news agency Itim quoted Arafat as saying that
"several problems still require a solution."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's aides charged Arafat for backtracking on compromise
language reached earlier this week on the extent of Israel's
commitment to a deadline for the Israeli troop redeployment in the
rest of West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian sources said that the Arafat-Ross meeting last
night was conducted in a tough atmosphere. The English daily The
Jerusalem Post quoted Arafat as telling Ross at one point that
"There are more burning issues than signing the agreement."
</P>
<P>
The alleged Arafat's hardening of position came after the
Wednesday shooting spree by an Israeli soldier in central Hebron
which wounded seven Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
A day earlier, negotiators had been confident that the terms
had been worked out on clinching a deal and an Arafat-Netanyahu
summit would sign it Thursday.
</P>
<P>
One Netanyahu aide said that the original terms did not
obligate Israel to a hard deadline for further redeployment
while they were also acceptable to the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Israel on Wednesday once again blamed the PA for delaying
the signing of Hebron agreement. David Bar-Ilan, Netanyahu's
media adviser, blamed the PA for applying the old tactics of
footdragging in order to bring more international pressure on
Israel so to squeeze out more concessions.
</P>
<P>
"It's quite clear that the stalling is done by the
Palestinian Authority. The reasonable guess is that they feel
that this situation of no agreement favors them and is
detrimental to us," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
