<HEADLINE> China Regulates Value-Added Tax on Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- China has issued a notice urging
taxation agencies nationwide to step up their effort for
collecting and regulating the value-added tax on land.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to make the most of the role of the tax in
standardizing the land and real estate markets, the State
Administration of Taxation said in the notice.
</P>
<P>
Most areas have done a great deal to formulate rules to
accelerate the collection process and to promptly hand over the
tax revenues to the state coffer, the notice said.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, collection of the tax is satisfactory," it said.
</P>
<P>
However, some areas have been slow and inefficient in
collecting the tax, the notice noted, urging taxation agencies to
check and register contracts for the transfer and development of
real estates.
</P>
<P>
"A full check and registration of such contracts signed before
January 1 of 1994 should be launched, in an effort to examine
their qualifications for tax exemptions," the notice said.
</P>
<P>
It asked all areas to establish and keep improving a tax
declaration system and other regulations and rules for the
value-added tax on land.
</P>
<P>
All areas should launch a check on payment of the tax and on
implementation the tax rules in the near future, the notice said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
