<HEADLINE> Third Israeli Arrested in Hebron Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 3 (Xinhua) -- A third Israeli soldier has
reportedly been questioned by the Israeli police after
Wednesday's shooting attack in the center of Hebron, which left
at least seven wounded.
</P>
<P>
According to an Israel Radio report this morning, the third
soldier, like Noam Friedman who carried out the shooting attack
Wednesday, is believed to serve in the Anatot army base on the
outskirts of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Friedman's close friend, 19-year-old soldier Yuval
Jibli, of Jerusalem, was also arrested, after Friedman told
investigators that Jibli knew his plans to kill Arabs in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Jibli, who also serves with Friedman at the Anatot army base
and reportedly went to an Arab village near his army base on
Wednesday and fired shots in the air, is suspected of "collusion
and failure to prevent a crime."
</P>
<P>
However, judge of the Petah Tikva Magistrate's Court only
agreed to remand Jibli for only four days, saying police did not
bring sufficient evidence for a longer remand.
</P>
<P>
Police refused to disclose exactly what proof they have that
Jibli knew of Friedman's plot, but a representative did say there
are indications of other conspiracies to harm Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Friedman who told reporters that he had fired to
thwart a redeployment agreement in Hebron, was to be remained
in custody until January 12 on suspicion of attempted murder
and incitement.
</P>
<P>
Police and the General Security Services also are
investigating whether more accomplices were involved in the
incident in Hebron and the possibility of a new Jewish
underground. 
</P>
</TEXT>
