<HEADLINE> Most Zambian School Leavers Can't Go to Varsities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Only 1,000 out of 12,000 grade
12 school leavers who qualify to the University of Zambia (UNZA)
will this year be admitted due to lack of sponsorship, Times of
Zambia today quoted Education Minister Syamukayumbu Syamujaye as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said here on Thursday that the government could not afford
tuition fees for all the pupils and at the same time the highest
institution of the country has no capacity to accommodate such a
big number of students.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that some of the 1,000 students to be
admitted to UNZA will have to pay for themselves because of
limitations in the budget.
</P>
<P>
''The bursaries committee and the Ministry of Education are
working out a mechanism to see how the two universities, (UNZA)
and Copperbelt University (CBU), can capture a big number of
students. The budget cannot capture all the students who
qualify,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Syamujaye confirmed that UNZA has increased tuition fees for
the forthcoming intake but did not say how much it is.
</P>
<P>
It is difficult for the government to open several
universities and so it is up to the private sector to takeerbelt the
challenge, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
There are only two universities in Zambia. 
</P>
