<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0700 GMT January 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Thousands of people went on a burning and looting
rampage Thursday in Sanggau Ledo district of West Kalimantan
province, Indonesia, the aftershock of ethnic tension that broke
out Monday claiming five lives, The Jakarta Post newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Prime Minister Deve Gowda is scheduled to
pay a two-day official visit to Bangladesh from January 6 for
furthering enhancing bilateral ties, official sources said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Cuba will form commissions to take the United States
to the court of justice so that citizens who are victims of
actions promoted or supported by Washington can present their
claims, the country's top legislator said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- The Peruvian government has appointed new police chiefs
to replace those who are still being held in hostage at the
Japanese ambassador's residence in Lima, local press reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
ROME -- About 60 kilograms of pure heroin were seized by
Italian police outside Bari Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The drug was hidden in a truck on the A-14 highway just a few
kilometers outside the provincial capital and the driver, a
Bulgarian citizen, was arrested.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. State Department on Thursday declined to
comment on two U.S. diplomats who have been reported to leave
India quietly as a result of links with an Indian intelligence
official.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The NATO-led Stabilization Force said Thursday it
would confiscate tank ammunition donated to the Muslim-Croat
Federation Army within a U.S. military aid program because the
ammunition had not been properly registered.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on Thursday extended
U.S. sanctions on Libya on the ground of what he said was the
crisis between the United States and Libya not being resolved.
</P>
