<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maize Yield May Drop in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Maize production may drop by 40
percent this year as more than 250,000 small-sized farms in
Zambia can't afford price-hiked fertilizer, the "Times of Zambia"
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Zambian National Farmers Union leader Ajay
Washee as saying that the maize output in the country may fall to
some 720,000 or 810,000 tons in 1997, down from 1.26 million tons
last year.
</P>
<P>
The expected decrease is majorly resulted by the new prices of
fertilizer, which doubled last month and caused a lot of
complaints from small farmers, the main producers of maize in
Zambia, said Washee.
</P>
<P>
It's a common knowledge that the small farms can't afford
fertilizer at so high prices, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The transportation of fertilizer is another question.
Fertilizer often arrives very late due to poor marketing
commercial system. And in most provinces, it even can't be in
farmers' hands due to the impassable roads there.
</P>
<P>
Only about 64 percent of the 1996 maize yield have been
marketed in Zambia, and the rest are restored by the farmers,
Washee added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Emphasizes Asset Administration for Economic Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The situation of an irrational state economic structure must
not continue, and we should make our management more
quality-oriented than quantity-oriented," said Vice-Minister of
Finance Zhang Youcai.
</P>
<P>
While actively promoting enterprise system reforms and making
good use of the increased value in state assets, China should
place emphasis on liquidating its available assets and resolutely
carry out the policy to restructure its state economy, said Zhang,
who is also director of the State Administration of State Property.
</P>
<P>
"This is aimed at optimizing the distribution of state assets
and is the fundamental way to fully tap the leading role of the
state economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The focus of restructuring the state economy lies in
reshuffling the organizational structure of enterprises as well as
the sectoral and regional structures, Zhang said, adding that all
should be done in line with the overall plan for restructuring the
national economy and state industrial policies.
</P>
<P>
Both the issues of immobility and loss of state assets should
be tackled in the process, and mergering, takeovers and
bankruptcies of existing enterprises should be employed, Zhang
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
