<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia to Send More Laborers Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia will send thousands
of young laborers abroad this year so as to solve the increasingly
serious unemployment problem in the country.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 400,000 people have been out of job,
accounting for 17 percent of its total population of 2.35 million,
a newspaper has quoted unofficial statistics as saying.
</P>
<P>
The State Great Hural has established a temporary committee for
seeking job opportunities and begun to work out a related national
action plan.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia has sent hundreds of thousands of laborers to
Kazakhstan under a Mongolian-Kazakh accord. It has also sent
laborers to South Korea and some Eastern European nations through
other ways.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 3,000 Mongolians working in South Korea
through non-governmental ways and South Korea has said that it
could accept 5,000 more Mongolians to work there.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Canada, some Southeast Asian nations and China's
Taiwan region have also said that they could accept Mongolian
laborers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
