<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Denies Involvement in Damascus Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Israel has denied involvement
in the Tuesday bus bombing in Damascus, capital of Syria, which
killed nine people and wounded 44 others, Israel Radio reported
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Following Syria's accusations against the Mossad, Israel's
intelligence service, for carrying out the bus bombing, Israeli
officials have dismissed the allegations as "ridiculous."
</P>
<P>
A statement by an unnamed government source, carried on the
official Syrian News Agency, said that "this terrorist, criminal,
cowardly act comes amid the escalation of Israeli threats by a
number of Israeli officials lately aiming to kill the peace
process."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Prime Minister's office said that there is no
basis in reality for the Syrian government to point a finger at
Israel as the responsible party for the attack.
</P>
<P>
David Bar Ilan, a senior aide to Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu, termed the Syrian allegation "sheer nonsense," while
the U.S. administration called on Syria to back up its
allegations.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said that it
was a very serious charge for one state to accuse another of
actually sponsoring bombing in its capital.
</P>
<P>
"The charge was wild and irresponsible if it was not back up
by evidence," Burns said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
