<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's State Loans Reach 55 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's accumulated foreign
debts and loans obtained from the internal capital market and
banks have reached 55 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Chairman of the Privatization Commission
Salman Shah in an interview at the local TV station Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Shah said that the government is trying to improve the
country's credit rating by bringing the figure down to 15 to 20
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The amount of accumulated loans could be cut considerably
through the process of privatization, Shah said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the financial situation of government departments,
such as the Heavy Mechanical Complex, the Karachi Electric Supply
Corporation and the Railways, have deteriorated to such an extent
that they cannot even pay salaries to their employees.
</P>
<P>
"It is not possible for the government to meet expenses by the
money collected through taxes and it is now essentially important
to privatize them," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to strengthen the Privatization Commission,"
Shah said, noting that a considerable amount of revenue can be
obtained to ease the burden of internal loans by selling out
profit-making state-owned units to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Shah also said that the government has tried to make the
process of privatization more transparent by increasing members of
the commission and giving representation to the private sector in
it at the time of the commission's re-organization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
