<HEADLINE> India Refuses to Comment on U.S. Spying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government and the
U.S. embassy here were non-committal on Thursday's press reports
that two U.S. diplomats have been asked by New Delhi to leave the
country for their alleged espionage activities, The Times of India
said today.
</P>
<P>
One of the two U.S. diplomats in question -- a woman in a
senior position in the embassy -- is allegedly the station
director of the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) in India
while the other is a junior diplomat, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the two were accused of "hobnobbing" with their
Indian contact Rattan Sehgal, chief of the Counter-Intelligence
Division of the Indian Intelligence Bureau (IB).
</P>
<P>
Sehgal has "opted" for retirement, highly placed intelligence
sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the U.S. embassy refused to comment anything on
the issue beyond saying that "the news report is an internal
Indian government matter."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a spokesman of the Indian Ministry of External
Affairs said that "it is the policy of the government of India not
to comment on such reports."
</P>
<P>
According to The Times of India, New Delhi's downplaying of the
episode is in line with its policy to tackle spying activities
involving "friendly countries" in a quiet manner.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
