<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Decade Sees Fastest Industrial Growth Rate for Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- In the past decade, Beijing's
industrial sector has scored its fastest growth rate in the
history of the capital city, according to a communique.
</P>
<P>
The communique was released by the municipal office in charge
of the city's third industry survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey, part of a national study, was conducted in the
first half of 1996 in accordance with a State Council decision.
</P>
<P>
Results showed that by the end of 1995, there were 34,293
industrial enterprises and production-type units in the city
proper, 5,894 more than in 1985. They had a total work force of
Over 2.4 million, up by 12.4 percent over 1985, and their assets
were valued at 269.7 billion yuan, up 8.1 times.
</P>
<P>
The city reported an industrial added value of 52.5 billion
yuan in 1995, an increase of 110 percent. The gross industrial
output value stood at more than 144 billion yuan, an increase of
2.1 times or an annual growth rate of nearly 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade or so, the state-run industry has maintained
its dominant status, in spite of the development of economies with
various ownerships. In 1995, the state-run sector accounted for
almost 73 percent of the gross industrial output value and 77
percent of the total assets in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of small enterprises grew in the industrial
sector. The number of light industries decreased, while that of
heavy industries rose, the results showed. The output value of the
heavy industry grew from 56.2 percent to 66.2 percent of the
total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
