<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Million out of Illiteracy in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- China met its expectations in
its campaign to wipe out illiteracy in 1996, providing educational
opportunities for more than four million people, an official with
the State Education Commission (SEC) said today.
</P>
<P>
To date, six percent of Chinese people aged 15 to 47 are
illiterate, down four percent in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The SEC official said the move to make nine-year compulsory
education universal and eliminate illiteracy among young and
middle-aged people by the end of this century has been progressing
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The two targets of the first phase have been basically reached,
with 1,400 counties, or half of China's population, having met the
state-set requirement by the end of 1996, he said. Five counties
in the Tibet Autonomous Region have promoted the need
for education at the secondary school level.
</P>
<P>
SEC, along with the Ministry of Finance and 12 provincial
governments, co-conducted an extensive poverty relief education
program, investing 5.3 billion yuan (about 640 million US dollars)
in total, he added.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that during the first half of the century,
illiterates in China made up 90 percent of the total
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
