<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Toy Company Increases Investment in Inland Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 3 (Xinhua) -- VTech Group of Companies, a
Hong Kong-based conglomerate for making electronic toys, has
nearly finished construction of a workshop in south China's
Guangdong Province in the company's new science and technology
park scheduled for completion in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
According to an executive of the conglomerate, the building has
a combined floor space of 170,000 sq m, and will be located in
"VTech Scientific and Technological Park" in Dongguan.
</P>
<P>
By then, the group's investment in inland areas will increase
from 800 million to 1.1 billion Hong Kong dollars.
</P>
<P>
Set up in 1976, VTech conglomerate is mainly engaged in
designing, manufacturing and marketing of high-tech electronic
products, including educational games, computer-related products,
and cordless telephones.
</P>
<P>
After more than two decades, the company has grown into Hong
Kong's largest electronic enterprise. In 1995, it scored 700
million U.S. dollars in total sales.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the workshops in the new park started in March
of 1996. Located 20 km away from the existing workshops on Houjie
Street, the park has a planned area of 66.6 hectares, with an
entire investment of 1.8 billion Hong Kong dollars. The cost of
first-stage construction is 300 million Hong Kong dollars.
</P>
<P>
When completed, the park will be able to accommodate
40,000 to 50,000 workers, and will feature workshops with a total
floor space of 800,000 sq m, and an industrial production area.
</P>
<P>
The executive contributed the group's flourishing business to
the reform and opening-up policies of the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
"After 1997, Hong Kong's industries and interior areas'
abundant raw materials, labor and technological resources will be
more closely combined, and competitiveness will be enhanced rather
than reduced," the executive said, adding that now is the best
time for increasing investment in inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, VTech has built workshops on Houjie Street in
Dongguan, which carry out the design, development, production,
quality control, packaging and export for most of the
conglomerate's products.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Hong Kong group does all of its manufacturing
and assembly business in these facilities, and has hired several
hundred engineers to develop new products in Shenzhen and Dongguan.
</P>
<P>
So far, workshops on Houjie Street have a total floor space of
280,000 sq m, generating five billion Hong Kong dollars of output
value each year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
