<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 Million Disaster Victims in China Well Accommodated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Many areas in China that were
stricken by severe natural disasters last year have maintained
sound social order, thanks to aid from the government and generous
public donations, an official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The 40 million hardest-hit disaster victims have been well
accommodated, provided with sufficient food, clothes, shelter and
medical care, and the public is calm," Fan Baojun, vice-minister
of Civil Affairs, said at a press conference today.
</P>
<P>
His remark was based on the ministry's recent inspection tours
in 14 provinces and autonomous regions where the most damage
occurred. The 40 million residents in those areas were most
heavily affected and in need of immediate help.
</P>
<P>
Relief funds from the central government in 1996 totaled 2.3
billion yuan (277 million US dollars), 21 percent more than the
budgeted sum, and 43 percent more than the amount earmarked in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Local governments at various levels also added 1.45 billion
yuan for the disaster victims.
</P>
<P>
The public donated 2.58 billion yuan in relief funds, and
overseas contributions came to 220 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister said that "public donations for the first
time exceeded the amount provided by the governments."
</P>
<P>
The sharp increase in public donations was due to a national
charity campaign promoted by President Jiang Zemin. Storehouses
for non-monetary donations have been set up in major cities and a
management system has taken shape.
</P>
<P>
In addition to frequent floods, droughts, typhoons and other
natural calamities, 26 earthquakes measuring over five on the
Richter Scale also shook the country, causing great loss of life
and property.
</P>
<P>
Fan said over 100 million victims were relocated as part of
emergency relief efforts last year, and the number of deaths and
injuries was cut to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
The local governments were encouraged to shoulder part of the
responsibility of rescuing disaster victims in their own regions,
so that the funds from the central government can be given to the
most needy.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide auditing networks to oversee the spending of
relief funds have ensured the money goes straight to the victims,
according to the vice-minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
