<HEADLINE> Air Traffic Safe in 1996 over Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai skies were reportedly
safe in 1996, despite the heavy air traffic over China's largest
city.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai air routes carried 168,000 airplanes in 1996, 15
percent more than in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The authorities attributed the safe year to the effective
precautions taken to detangle increasingly busy airways. As part
of the effort, one of the air passages leading to the Hongqiao
Airport was removed.
</P>
<P>
On the busiest routes, between Shanghai and Beijing, and
between Shanghai and Guangzhou, certain planes are required to fly
at designated altitudes, which shortens flying time and increases
the flow of air traffic.
</P>
<P>
A fan-shape air traffic control area has been opened
specifically for planes traveling south from Shanghai, where the
airways are excessively crowded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
