<HEADLINE> Land Remains National Property in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Minister for
Agriculture and Co-operatives Njelu Kasaka has said the government
will continue to own land, because it is national asset and has not
plans of selling it to any individual, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said this when talking to employees of the
National Ranch Corporation (NARCO), at Ruvu on Tuesday at the
beginning of his tour of Kibaha and Bagamoyo districts, in Coast
Region.
</P>
<P>
He was briefing NARCO employees on the new privatisation policy
which he said should spare selling land to individuals.
</P>
<P>
Kasaka added that this cannot be felt as a problem at the moment
since the country's population is relatively small. But, he said in
50 yeas to come, the population may have more than doubled, and
people will still need land for their development.
</P>
<P>
It would be unwise to let someone own a piece of land even when he
did not make use of it, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the deputy minister advised the workers to buy shares in
the corporations which will be soon privatised.  enditem

