<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba to Host Two Large Tourism Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Cuba will host a regional forum,
and a major national convention on tourism promotion in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
The 11th Congress of the Confederation of Latin American
Tourism Organizations (Cotal '97) will be held on May 12 to 17 in
Havana.
</P>
<P>
It will be the third international tourism meeting there since
last March.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of Cotal will coincide with Cuba's 18th Tourism
Convention, the most important annual commercial exchange in this
Caribbean island, said Fausto Garcia, the forum organizing
committee president.
</P>
<P>
As some 1,500 travel agents were expected to attend both
meetings, Cuba would take advantage of the occasion to intensify
the promotion of local tourism, which had been a consistent
foreign exchange earner for the Cuban economy since 1995, Garcia
said.
</P>
<P>
The year 1996 saw many foreign companies invest in this
tropical island. An Italy company paid 16 million U.S. dollars in
May for a resort called "Mediclub", while Vancouver-based Wilton
Properties Ltd. invested 200 million dollars to cooperate in a
Cuban tourist resort, last July.
</P>
<P>
Last March the U.S. Congress approved the Helms-Burton Bill
threatening to punish foreign companies who do business with Cuba,
and was heavily criticized for this extraterritorial measure.
</P>
<P>
Cuba hosted a venture in culture tourism in Latin American and
Caribbean countries last November and the Second Iberoamerican
Meeting for the Development of Tourism in last March.
</P>
<P>
Cotal, the highest ranking regional tourism organization, is
formed by private enterprises in 21 countries. Its slogan for the
coming congress is "Forty years of tourism promotion in Latin
America."
</P>
<P>
Cotal annual forums, of which Cuba was the founder, will
return to Havana after 37 years. Cuba attended the Lima Meeting in
1993, said Garcia.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that in 1996 more than one million
foreign tourists visited Cuba. It was the largest number yet and a 30
percent increase over 1995. The island also enjoyed a growth of
7.8 percent in gross domestic product during the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
