<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Prospects for Thai Bourse Remain Dim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The prospects for Thailand's
bourse in the Year of the Ox did not look bullish when share
prices dropped as much as 3.42 percent Thursday, the first trading
day of the new year.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index plunged 28.44 points
before the market closed at 803.13 points, a 51-month low.
</P>
<P>
On September 11, 1992 the indicator closed lower at 801.90
points.
</P>
<P>
Just minutes before the market closed Thursday, the index fell
below the 800-point psychological level, but bounced back on
bargain-hunting at the end of the day, in the worst year-opening
performance in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
The Thai bourse, hit by heavy declines in major overseas
markets and on weak Thai economic indicators, had a thin turnover
of 2.25 billion baht (88.24 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
On December 30, the last trading day of last year, the SET
closed at 831.57 points, only 4.14 points lower, with a trading
turnover of 4.7 billion baht (184.31 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the SET shed a total of 520.30 points, or 39.31
percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Thursday investors sold out on concern of
Thai economic indicators. Investors, especially foreigners, were
concerned about the country's high current account deficit and
falling exports.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index as announced by the Commerce Ministry
rose 4.8 percent year-on-year in December, unchanged from
November.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors, having been net sellers most of last year,
continued their sell-off Thursday. SET officials have been talking
about finding ways to reduce foreign investors' influence on the
bourse.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said sellers unloaded finance, bank and property
sectors after they bought them late last month.
</P>
<P>
The finance sector led the decline, losing 8.16 percent, the
property dipped 4.33 percent and the banking slipped 3.23
percent.
</P>
<P>
The finance sector's performance indicated that "loss-cutting"
rather than "profit-taking" was the reason behind the selling
pressure, according to Thanawat Patchimkul, an analyst with
Seamico Securities.
</P>
<P>
He felt the SET index could drop to 750 points in the next six
months as concerns over "window dressing" of institutional
investors' balance sheets and earnings growth heighten in the
first quarter and foreign investors continue to prefer other Asian
markets to the Thai bourse.
</P>
<P>
Brokers expected sustained selling pressure until the current
account deficit and exports showed improving trends. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
