<HEADLINE> Indian PM to Visit Bangladesh Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Deve
Gowda is scheduled to pay a two-day official visit to Bangladesh
from January 6 for furthering enhancing bilateral ties, official
sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The visit assumes significance as it comes close on the heels
of the historic 30-year Ganges water-sharing agreement signed
between India and Bangladesh on December 12 during the visit of
Bangladesh Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina to India.
</P>
<P>
Gowda will be accompanied by a high-level delegation comprising
External Affairs Minister I.K. Gujral, Home Minister Indrajit
Gupta, Foreign Secretary Salman Haider, Commerce Secretary P.
Prabhu and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Chakma refugee problems and optimum utilization of water
resources are likely to figure prominently during the talks
between the prime ministers of the two countries. India has been
asking Bangladesh for long to take back the Chakma refugees, who
are currently sheltered in camps in India's Tripura state.
</P>
<P>
When asked if any agreement between the two countries was on
the cards, official sources have said that as of now, nothing had
been finalized but all would depend on talks between Gowda and
Hasina.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Bangladesh, the Indian prime minister
besides meeting Bangladeshi leaders would address the Bangladesh
Federation of Industry, Chambers and Commerce in a bid to enhance
bilateral economic and trade relations, official sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
