<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Minister List Economic Priorities in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Keeping down inflation, reforming
fiscal system and public administration, and keeping up production
and consumption are the Italian government's priorities in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Industry Minister Pierluigi Bersani made the remarks today
during a television interview, where he defended the government's
year-end fiscal decree and package of incentives.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal decree and package of incentives, designed to rescue
industrial sectors in crisis, are labeled by business and industry
circles as "going in the right direction but inadequate."
</P>
<P>
In his response, Bersani said the incentives valued at 1.78
trillion lire (1.17 billion U.S. dollars) and bonuses for new car
sales are "only a wedge in the government's industrial policy."
</P>
<P>
The first thing, he said, is to hold the ground already won in
lowering annual inflation down to around 3.8 percent in 1996, in
stabilizing the lire and in trimming interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The second, the minister noted, is to move on to an overhaul of
the fiscal system and the public administration, which will affect
the enterprising system in areas of employment and privatization.
</P>
<P>
The third priority is, Bersani said, "to give tone to 1997
because we are at a crucial passage, a difficult and sensitive
one, which requires support of production and consumption."
</P>
<P>
Bersani said the government's year-end fiscal decree was based
on the belief that 1997 "will be a year of recovery, for working
together" among all sides who take roles in economic activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
