<HEADLINE> Nepali Ruling Party Expects Five More Parliament Seats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main ruling party
expects to become the largest party in Parliament by winning all
the five vacant seats of the lower house to be elected in the
upcoming by-elections, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sher bahadur Deuba's Nepali Congress (NC) party,
which has 86 MPs in the powerful lower house, would concentrate
on the by-elections scheduled for later this month, newspapers
said.
</P>
<P>
After a Central Working Committee (CWC) meeting of the NC party
Thursday, a party spokesman said that the NC has given top-most
priority to the by-elections for five vacant house seats and hopes
to win all of the them.
</P>
<P>
Rumors here said that the NC party might press Prime Minister
Deuba to call for mid-term elections as his three-party coalition
government only has minority support in Parliament after a
no-confidence vote last week.
</P>
<P>
The 205-seat lower house Tuesday last week rejected a
no-confidence motion tabled by main opposition the Communist Party
of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML), which has 88 MPs in
the house, with a vote of 101 MPs in favor and 84 MPs against the
motion. The motion required a majority of 103 votes to pass in the
house.
</P>
<P>
However, the NC spokesman Thursday said that the option of
mid-term elections was not the topic of the discussions at the
party's CWC meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
