<HEADLINE> Unrest Flares up in West Kalimantan, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people went on a
burning and looting rampage Thursday in Sanggau Ledo district of
West Kalimantan province, Indonesia, the aftershock of ethnic
tension that broke out Monday claiming five lives, The Jakarta
Post newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
At 6:00 p.m., a mob of about 5,000 people were still rampaging
through the streets of the districts of Bengkayang and Samalantan,
and the villages of Marabu, Kampung Tengah and Jirak, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Most of the mob were men of the Dayak ethnic group. Of those
who died, two were Dayaks. The other three originated from Madura
Island, East Java. In addition, at least nine people were injured
with varying degrees of severity.
</P>
<P>
There were also "countless" houses being burned down by
rioters, the paper quoted a source in Marabu village as saying.
</P>
<P>
A curfew was imposed on the area Thursday. Neither the local
military office nor Regent Taryo Aryanto could be contacted for
confirmation last night, it added.
</P>
<P>
A mobile brigade and members of Battalion No. 643 have been
dispatched from the provincial capital of Pontianak, some 700
kilometers north of Jakarta, to contain the unrest.
</P>
<P>
The tension in Sanggau Ledo was sparked Monday by a brawl over
a woman between two groups of youths. In the incident that
occurred during a folk show, a Madura man reportedly stabbed two
Dayak tribesmen in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
News about the brawl circulated rapidly and prompted more
violence Tuesday and the days after. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
