<HEADLINE> Philippines Expects Sharp Rise in Fiscal Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
expected to register a fiscal surplus of at least 22.82 billion
pesos (870 million U.S. dollars) in 1997, according to the
Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The projection more than tripled the expected surplus of 6.91
billion pesos (263 million dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Finance officials said the larger surplus would dampen the need
for the government to borrow, an activity which always drives up
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the fiscal balance of the government had been
in constant surplus since 1994 when the government enjoyed its
first surplus of 16.3 billion pesos (622 million dollars). In
1995, the fiscal surplus was 10.2 billion pesos (389 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The original target of the government fiscal surplus this year
was set at only 14.7 billion pesos (561 million dollars) but it
was later revised because the Comprehensive Tax Reform Program is
expected to be fully implemented this year and allow the
government to receive more revenues.
</P>
<P>
The country's fiscal surplus in 1996 is expected to be only
6.91 billion pesos instead of the targeted 17.5 billion pesos (667
million dollars) partly because of lower privatization proceeds
and accelerated infrastructure spending, the officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
