<HEADLINE> Bhutanese Refugees End Sit-in at Nepal-India Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Bhutanese refugees Thursday
called off their marathon sit-in protest at the Nepal-India
border, easing the tension at the eastern border area of Nepal in
the last few days, said a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of refugees had staged a sit-in at the Mechi bridge
since last Sunday, protesting against the forced deportation of
some 850 Bhutanese refugees from two camps in the Indian state of
West Bengal to Nepal by Indian police.
</P>
<P>
The protesters called off the sit-in Thursday after claiming
that the Indian side admitted its fault in deporting these
Bhutanese refugees.
</P>
<P>
They also allowed 13 Indian buses, used by the Indian police to
carry the deported refugees into the Nepali territory, to return
to India.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the refugees had said they would free the buses only
after India agrees to transport the deportees back to India.
</P>
<P>
The five-day stand-off at the Mechi bridge had paralyzed
transport in the border area and caused inconvenience to local
people, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Appeal Movement Coordination Council (AMCC),
a Bhutanese refugee group, said that the sit-in was called off
after series of dialogues between the AMCC and the Indian police.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indian police admitted they were wrong in deporting
the refugees.
</P>
<P>
However, a high-ranking Indian police officer denied any
understanding between the refugees and the Indian police, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees have been staying in Nepal and
India, most of them in eight refugee camps in eastern Nepal, since
they fled Bhutan six years ago due to the "one nation, one people"
policy adopted by the Bhutanese authorities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
