<HEADLINE> Cuba to Form Commissions to Sue United States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Cuba will form commissions to
take the United States to the court of justice so that citizens
who are victims of actions promoted or supported by Washington can
present their claims, the country's top legislator said today.
</P>
<P>
Ricardo Alarcon de Quesada, president of the National Assembly
of People's Power, said the commissions will be authorized to
decide the validity of the demands, as well as the responsibility
of the U.S. government in the cases raised by Cuban citizens.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the commissions followed the "Law of
Reaffirmation of Cuban Dignity and Sovereignty," which was
approved by the National Assembly on December 24, as a
countermeasure against the Helms-Burton Act of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly presidency and the Ministry of Justice
have started working on the prompt formation of the commissions,
which will bring together all the claims made by both private
parties and the Cuban government, Ricardo Alarcon said.
</P>
<P>
Under the new Cuban law, any future negotiations on
compensating the U.S. properties nationalized by the Cuban
government will, first of all, have to take into account the
damages inflicted on Cuba by U.S. armed actions, sabotage, trade
embargo, punitive measures and aggressions of all kinds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
