<HEADLINE> Mexican Airline Enters Peruvian Air Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Peruvian government has issued
a license for a Mexican commercial carrier to provide passenger,
cargo and mail transport services to and from Peru.
</P>
<P>
The three-year license effective immediately stems from an
earlier agreement between the governments of Peru and Mexico,
local press reports today quoted government sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the bilateral agreement, the Peruvian Communications and
Transports Ministry allows Mexicana to fly round trips between
Lima and Cancun, a Mexican resort city, seven times a week.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Mexican airline is also approved to fly twice
a week between Lima and the Argentine capital city of Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
However, Mexicana is not allowed to offer direct or indirect
air transport services to and from Peru via an unauthorized third
country.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 foreign carriers are now operating in Peru,
including American Airlines of the United States, Lufthansa of
Germany, British Airways of Britain, and Aeroflot of Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
