<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Calls for Movement Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Nationalist Party
(BNP), the country's main opposition, called for a united movement
against the government in a resolution published here today.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said that Bangladesh's "public life has been
virtually paralyzed due to the wrong policy, and undemocratic and
fascist behavior of the present government."
</P>
<P>
The BNP and its front organizations held a joint meeting
Thursday and discussed the overall political, economic and law and
order situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The present government has revived its fascist and autocratic
character by unleashing torture and arrest on BNP leaders and
workers and filing false cases against them. Even BNP Chairperson
Begum Khaleda Zia was not spared," said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the opposition party announced a fresh agitation
program to hold demonstrations and rallies on January 5 and 6 in
districts and stage protests in the capital city of Dhaka on
January 7.
</P>
<P>
In early November last year, BNP MPs walked out of the house to
press for the party's 10-point demands, including a "neutral role"
of the speaker and the state-run Bangladesh TV and halting
"repression" on its workers.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating the party's willingness to give the parliamentary
democracy a solid foundation by making the house effective, BNP
Secretary General Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan urged the government to
accept the demands immediately.  
</P>
</TEXT>
