<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Closes 1996 With High Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Colombia closed 1996
with a 21.63 percent inflation, 4.63 percent over the target set
by the Bank of the Republic board of directors, said the National
Statistics Administrative Department (DANE) today.
</P>
<P>
Two percentage points over 1995, the annual inflation means
that if a Colombian had to make ends meet on 100,000 pesos (about
100 U.S. dollars) in January of 1996, he or she will have to spend
121,630 pesos (some 121.63 dollars) today for the same necessities.
</P>
<P>
However, the last month of 1996 saw a 0.72 percent inflation,
the lowest monthly average in the last 13 years, due to the fall
of the prices of some agricultural products that otherwise could
go up on a seasonal basis in December, DANE said in a report.
</P>
<P>
Overall in 1996, the official report said, the sectors that
contributed most to the increase in the cost of living were house
rent, public services and education.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Colombian government announced that surveillance
over those sectors will be stepped up to prevent price rises
surpassing the 18 percent target set for 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
