<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exit from IMF Programs to Top Manila's 1997 Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The exit of the Philippines from
the stringent economic programs imposed by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) will dominate Manila's economic agenda in
1997, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We've been bullishly preparing for this exit because this will
mean the eventual economic liberation and independence of our
country," Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the IMF-approved three-year exit program, the Philippines
will finally get out of the IMF clutches in June 1997, ending more
than two decades of almost uninterrupted recourse to its programs.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the IMF programs contained stringent
conditions that have ensured the country's repayment of foreign
debts but limited its economic growth.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo said the country's exit from the IMF programs has
been propelled largely by its export and investment-led economic
growth, growing international reserves, and greatly improved
fiscal position.
</P>
<P>
According to De Ocampo, the primary task of the government in a
post-IMF era is the establishment of fiscal responsibility and
monetary restraint to ensure the country's capacity to stand on
its own.
</P>
<P>
To secure the fiscal stability, De Ocampo said the government
has to work for the enactment of the three-pronged Comprehensive
Tax Reform Program, which is expected to increase government
revenues by more than 2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country's monetary restraint has been enhanced
by the creation of an independent central monetary authority --
the Philippine Central Bank, which has been observing its mandate
to maintain a lower inflation and a stable foreign exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
