<HEADLINE> Puerto Rico's Re-elected Governor Plans Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Governor of Puerto Rica,
Pedro Rosello, started his second four-year mandate today
following his re-election in the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
Rosello hopes to achieve during his second term the reform of
his country's legislative system which maintains Puerto Rico as a
free United States associated state, the official news agency of
Cuba, Prensa Latina, said today.
</P>
<P>
Rosello, President of the National Progressive Party which
supports statehood, won 130,000 votes, six percent more than his
opponent from the Popular Democratic Party in last year's
elections.
</P>
<P>
A proposal presented by the new governor in 1993 aimed at
turning Puerto Rico into the 51st American Union state was
defeated by a small margin, 48 percent against 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the official strategy includes the possibility of
calling for new consultation on the constitution of the islands in
1998.
</P>
<P>
A Washington bid for a referendum on the matter failed last
year.
</P>
<P>
The Caribbean country became a self-governing commonwealth in
1952. Since then, it has remained in free association with the
United States as an "unincorporated territory". It is represented
in the U.S. House of Representatives by a popularly elected
Resident Commissioner who may vote on all aspects of legislation
except the final passage of a bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
