<HEADLINE> University Helps Train Tibetan Personnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Qinghai Normal University in
northwest China's Qinghai Province has helped train a large group
of Tibetan officials and teachers, adding some muscle to the
province's social development.
</P>
<P>
According to an official, the university first set up classes
for the ethnic minorities in the province's middle schools in
1982, intending to provide enough qualified teachers for the vast
pastoral area.
</P>
<P>
People in ethnic minorities account for 42 percent of the
population of the province, which is situated on the
Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau, known as the "roof of the World."
</P>
<P>
Over 400 graduates from Qinghai Normal University are now
working in secondary middle schools both in and outside the
province, and are qualified to lecture in both the Chinese and the
Tibetan language. 
