<HEADLINE> Peruvian Government Appoints New Police Chiefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Peruvian government has
appointed new police chiefs to replace those who are still being
held in hostage at the Japanese ambassador's residence in Lima.
</P>
<P>
Gen. Marcelo Nakamura Sakamoto will head anti-terrorism
activities and Gen. Denis del Castillo Valdivia, a former chief of
the National Intelligence Service, will lead anti-drug operations,
the local press reported today quoting informed police sources.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Gen. Arturo Marquina Gonzalez will be the new
national security chief and Gen. Fernando Gamero Febres will act
as the commander of the Seventh National Peruvian Police Region
headquartered in Lima.
</P>
<P>
Guerrillas of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA)
stormed Ambassador Morihisa Aoki's residence on December 17,
holding more than 500 people at a cocktail reception in hostage,
including high-ranking diplomats from Peru, Japan and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
The MRTA members have promised to free all hostages on the
condition that their imprisoned comrades are released by the
Peruvian government.
</P>
<P>
Three weeks into the crisis, a total of 74 hostages now still
remain in the sieged residence while others have been set free.
</P>
