<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Implements New Regulation to Help Handicapped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, January 3 (Xinhua) -- A new employment regulation in
north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region will give
handicapped people more job opportunities in government
institutions and businesses.
</P>
<P>
On January 1, the regional government put into effect a
regulation which requires that all government institutions and
enterprises provide employment opportunities to the handicapped,
who should make up at least 1.5 percent of the total number of
employees.
</P>
<P>
There are now 964,000 handicapped residents in Inner Mongolia,
accounting for 4.22 percent of its total population; 493,000 are
capable of working.
</P>
<P>
In the past, governments at various levels have started welfare
enterprises and worked out preferential policies to raise the
employment rate of the handicapped. However, 273,000 people are
still without jobs.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulation, handicapped people must be
actively recruited for positions in the government operations.
</P>
<P>
The work units which cannot meet their quota must pay
compensation to the employment agencies for the handicapped, in
accordance with local wage standards. Those violating the
regulation will be fined.
</P>
<P>
"The handicapped enjoy the same right to work as other
citizens, and both government and society have been offering
special aid and protection to the special groups," said Wang
Jinlong, an official with the region's Federation for the
Handicapped.
</P>
<P>
This year, the region will earmark 500,000 yuan to help some
handicapped residents find work. And labor service institutions
will be set up across the region, Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
