<HEADLINE> Panama Canal Tolls Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Panama Canal Commission
applied the first rise in the canal tolls on the New Year's Day, a
canal spokesman announced today.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the Board of Directors in December, in Miami,
the United States, the Panama Canal Authority, approved a series
of increases in the tolls to enable it to renew equipment, to meet
the requirements of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
"The first increase applied on January 1 represents an 8.2
percent rise over the former fee. Another 7.5 percent increase
will be applied in January of 1998, said the authority, which is
made up of Panamanian specialists and the U.S. Army Southern
Command Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
The toll for each ton of cargo increased from 2.21 U.S. dollars
to 2.39 dollars, while the tonnage fee for crossing the canal
without cargo rose to 1.9 dollars from the previous 1.76 dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The incomes from the toll increase will be used in financing
modernization and improvement programs for the Panama Canal," the
spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
