<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Thai Government Aims to Keep Inflation at 5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Thai Commerce Minister
Narongchai Akrasanee said the country's 5.9 percent inflation last
year was a positive trend for the new year.
</P>
<P>
Inflation for 1997 would be more stable and could be capped at
5 percent, the Bangkok Post today quotes the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Price rises last year increased by a satisfactory 5.9 percent,
slightly up on the forecast 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts blamed the heavy flooding in late 1995 for the hefty
consumer price index rises in the first quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 food and beverage index increased by 8.9 percent, with
the greatest growth in rice and flour of 16.7 percent, followed by
cooked food, 9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The non-food index rose by 3.7 percent, with entertainment and
the education sector having the highest growth of 8.2 percent and
tobacco and alcoholic drinks 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The wholesale price index for last year was 4.7 percent, with
agriculture and food products increasing in price by 8.6 percent
and industrial products by 2.4 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
