<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The State Council, China's highest governing body, has
issued a circular urging central government departments and
provincial governments to stabilize prices during the Spring
Festival, which is one month away.
</P>
<P>
The circular asks that government officials to make sure that
food and other goods will be in sufficient supply and that prices
will not rise again during the festival.
</P>
<P>
-- A frontpage commentary entitled "Try to Improve the
Efficiency in Opening Up," said that to taking effective measures
to improve the efficiency in opening-up is not only conducive to
the sound development of China's national economy, but to gearing
China's economy with the economy of the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- China's grain output hit a record 480 billion kilograms and
the annual per-capita net income of peasants is expected to reach
1,900 yuan in 1996, up by eight percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
-- In a move to promote the sustainable and steady development
of residential housing construction, the State Planning Commission
and the Ministry of Finance have jointly issued a circular
announcing the decision to cancel 48 irrational charges on
residential housing construction.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Ministry of Railways plans to improve rail transport
links between the Chinese mainland and Hong Kong. As part of the
plan, the ministry will open passenger train services linking
Beijing and Kowloon. Shanghai and Kowloon will also be linked to
facilitate traffic before July 1, 1997. 
