<HEADLINE> Muster Moves into Quater-finals at Qatar Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Thomas Muster, angered
by mobile phone users, dropped a set and took more than two hours
to beat Norway's Christian Ruud for a place in the quarter-finals
of the Qatar Open in Doha on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian needed two hours and 13 minutes to defeat Ruud
6-2, 3-6, 7-5 and set up a last eight clash against American Jim
Courier, the eighth seed.
</P>
<P>
Muster cruised through the first set in just 32 minutes but his
game went to pieces in the second when he became increasingly
disgruntled by line calls and the constant ringing of mobile
telephones inside the stadium court.
</P>
<P>
At one stage, the Austrian screamed at a spectator: "Turn off
your phone or get the hell out of here!"
</P>
<P>
Courier made the last eight with a 6-3, 6-4 win over Romanian
qualifier Razvan Sabau. Czech defending champion Petr Korda saw
off Magnus Norman of Sweden 6-7 (3-7), 6-4, 6-2 while Sergi
Bruguera defeated fellow Spaniard Javier Sanchez 6-0, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
In Friday's quarter-finals, Muster takes on Courier, Bruguera
meets Korda, Sweden's number five seed Magnus Gustafsson faces
Britain's Tim Henman and Morocco's Hicham Arazi plays Sweden's
Magnus Larsson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
