<HEADLINE> Brighter Prospects For Poor Women In Lhasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- A project to help mothers who are
poor has been launched in Lhasa, the capital of the Tibet Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
As the political, economic, and cultural center of the region,
Lhasa has seen rapid economic growth and improvements in living
standards in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In spite of this, there are 25,000 mothers in the plateau
city's urban and suburban areas who still live under the poverty
line, trying to care for their family members, especially the
young.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to raise money both in China and
abroad, to help mothers without sufficient means participate in
social and economic activities in a better way, and to improve
their education and health, making them aware of the importance of
a healthy child.  
</P>
