<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Chinese City Combating Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Huangshi, a raw materials producer
on the middle reaches of the Yangtze River, in China's Hubei
Province, now has cleaner air as a result of increased
environmental pollution control efforts.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, the city, which has a lot of
metallurgical industry because of non-ferrous ore found nearby,
invested 48.29 million yuan (one U.S. dollar equals to 8.3 Chinese
yuan) in dealing with 247 pollution sources from 1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
The city has also adopted measures to prevent new pollution,
and environmental protection has become a must in designs for all
new industrial projects.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1995, the city started 57 new projects, with a
total investment of one billion yuan, 55.5 million yuan of which was
spent on building of environmental protection facilities.
</P>
<P>
While increasing environmental pollution awareness, the city
authorities have also encouraged local industries to
turn potential pollution sources into commodities with economic
benefits.
</P>
<P>
The Daye Non-Ferrous Metal Company, for example, recycled the
sulfur dioxide it discharges to produce sulphuric acid, using 95
percent of the former polluter, while the Huangshi Power Plant
turned coal dust into walling materials, with a utilization ratio
of 63 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
