<HEADLINE> Soeharto: ASEAN Has lots of Things to Do </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
said Indonesia and Thailand as well as other member countries of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) still have a
lot of things to do to reach its goals.
</P>
<P>
"Like Thailand, Indonesia also sees ASEAN as a pole for the
implementation of our foreign policies. We should therefore
continue to strengthen our relations to reach ASEAN's goal," the
president said in a welcome dinner hosted in honor of Thai Prime
Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh at the Merdeka Palace here last
night.
</P>
<P>
He said ASEAN had brought great benefits to Southeast Asia
since its establishment 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The first informal summit of ASEAN which was held in Jakarta in
November, 1996 after the formal summit of the regional grouping in
Bangkok in December, 1995, produced various decisions including
the plan to expand its membership up to 10 countries.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
"The prestigious achievement of ASEAN had further strengthened
our relations in various fields in efforts to create peace,
stability and prosperity in Southeast Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Soeharto said, Indonesia and Thailand had for a long
time established close bilateral economic relations.
</P>
<P>
As many as 26 Thai companies are running their business in
Indonesia and 12 Indonesian companies are operating in Thailand,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit arrived here on Thursday for a two-day visit to
Indonesia. this is his first overseas visit since he was appointed
prime minister of a coalition government on December 1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto and Chavalit are scheduled to hold formal talks this
morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
