<DOCNO> XIE19970103.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rio Begins Year with Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Three of Rio de Janeiro's
four leading clubs have threatened to boycott this year's state
championship because they don't agree with the rules of the
competition.
</P>
<P>
In a row that has almost become a part of local soccer
tradition, Flamengo, Fluminense and Botafogo said they would walk
out on the tournament unless the Rio de Janeiro federation backed
down on a decision made on Monday to change the rules.
</P>
<P>
"This state championship is financial suicide," said Flamengo
director Michel Assef on Thursday, referring to the new set of
rules. "We will not accept this formula under any circumstances."
</P>
<P>
Originally, the federation had agreed a somewhat strange
formula under which the 12 clubs would take part in the first
stage with the major four -- Flamengo, Fluminense, Botafogo and
Vasco da Gama -- automatically going into the second stage. They
would be joined by the best four of the remaining clubs. The
second stage would then have been contested on a straightforward
round-robin basis.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, approved at a meeting on Monday, the
winners of the first stage will meet the winners of the second
stage in a final which will decide the competition.
</P>
<P>
Under the original option, the first stage would have been
merely academic for the major clubs.
</P>
<P>
But this suited Flamengo, Fluminense and Botafogo, who had
planned to field junior teams and send their first-choice squads
to play in a more lucrative Rio-Sao Paulo tournament and
friendlies around the country.
</P>
<P>
Arguments over the formula of the competition, which varies
from year to year, take place almost annually.
</P>
<P>
The formulas are decided at rowdy meetings which frequently
turn into battles between an alliance of Vasco and the smaller
clubs on one hand and Flamengo, Fluminense and Botafogo on the
other.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the only major country to hold regional
championships, which take place in the first half of the year.
The Brazilian championship itself lasts for just four months.
</P>
<P>
There has been criticism of the system for years, with the
major sides complaining that the regional championships force them
into too many loss-making fixtures against minor sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
