<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimming Coach Predicts Performance in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- "Altough they are young, they
are part of China's best. Let's see how they can do at the World
Cup meet here," Deputy Head Coach Zhang Xiong of the Chinese
national swimming team said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang told reporters after the Chinese arrived at the Kai Tak
airport this afternoon for the coming Epson Swimming World Cup
Hong Kong '97, the opening leg of this year's eight-leg World Cup
short course swimming series.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 13-swimmer team are teenagers, among whom were such
Olympians as female swimmers Nian Yun, 14, and Chen Yan, 17.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the main purpose of his team here is to have
the younger ones tested for getting mature. He admitted that it's
hard for some of the national team's veteran members to hang on
till the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000.
</P>
<P>
"We have to get ourselves ready as early as possible for the
Games," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the national team's elite members are to be sent to the
six European stops of the series in such cities as Espoo of
Finland, Malmo of Sweden and Paris.
</P>
<P>
As for the national swimming team, the Eight National Games
slated for October in Shanghai is the number one event on the
year's calendar. "We have to arrange our training and
competitions with priority left on the Games," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also said that some of the current team here would be
part of an elite task force which sets its sight on Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the performance by a relatively young side at last
summer's Olymoic Games in Atlanta, Zhang said that the swimmers
did what they could, although short of somwhat too high an
expectation from home.
</P>
<P>
With only three of the 21 Olympic swimers being from the last
Olympics, Zhang said it was almost impossible for them to achieve
what Chinese swimmers had at Barclona.
</P>
<P>
The current younng swimmers are realy doing well, both through
international competitions," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
"That's the only way to get mature," he added.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Hong Kong meet starts on Saturday. A
record-setting entry of 28 teams is to be fielded, according to
the organizers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
