<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Declines Comment on Diplomats Involving in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. State Department on
Thursday declined to comment on two U.S. diplomats who have been
reported to leave India quietly as a result of links with an
Indian intelligence official.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing, State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns
told reporters: "I really have not much to give you on that,
except to say that, from what I understand, this is an internal
decision -- internal affair of the Indian government."
</P>
<P>
India's newspaper Hindustan Times reported on Thursday that
Indian would ask two U.S. diplomats to leave after an Indian
intelligence official was accused of having unauthorized links
with them.
</P>
<P>
Burns told the reporters at the briefing that the State
Department "may have some information, but we're not willing to
share it" with others.
</P>
<P>
Burns said he was not aware of anyone being asked to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
