<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns against Syrian Charges on Israel over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- the United States on Thursday
cautioned Syria against unsubstantialed accusations of Israeli
agents for a bomb attack in Damascus earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, Syria blamed Israel's secret service for a
bus bombing in Damascus on the New Year's Eve, that killed nine
people and injured 44.
</P>
<P>
Syria issued an statement following the Bus blast, saying:
"Mossad agents took the opportunity of preparations for
celebrating the new year and the gathering of people... and put a
bomb inside a bus, which exploded shortly after the bus began
moving...."
</P>
<P>
The Syrian Arab News Agency accused the Mossad, the Israeli
intelligence service, of setting off the explosion, saying: "this
terrorist, criminal, cowardly act comes amid the escalation of
Israeli threats by a number of Israeli officials lately aiming to
kill the peace process."
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns, in answering
reporters' questions on the incident, said: "It is a very serious
charge for one state to accuse another of actually sponsoring
bombings in its capital."
</P>
<P>
"If the Syrian government and the Syrian press cannot back up
what they are saying, well they ought not to make that charge.
It's a wild and irresponsible charge if in fact it is not backed
up by evidence," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
