<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Avoids Steep Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 2, (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average avoided another steep drop at the first trading session of
1997 today under a late round of buying spree.
</P>
<P>
But most stock measures suffered sizable losses after another
unexpectedly strong economic reading heightened worries about
inflation and sent interest rates soaring in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow lost 5.78 to 6,442.49, having bounced back from an
88-point deficit over the last 30 minutes. The blue-chip barometer
slid more than 95 points in the morning after a surprisingly
robust report on the manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 12-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, NYSE volume totaled 461.03 million
shares, more than 395.21 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 3.75 to 736.99, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 2.77 to 389.53.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 10.33 to 1,280.70, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.18 to 569.16.
</P>
<P>
Dow plunged 101 points at its year-end sell-off on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Purchasing Management reported a
strong manufacturing economy and also a jump in costs for
manufacturing supplies.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell today, the yield on the 30-year Treasury
bond jumped as high as 6.76 percent, up from late Tuesday's 6.64
percent. By late afternoon, the yield stood at 6.74 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the Labor Department reported today that first time claims
for unemployment benefits rose to the highest level since summer.
And early reports from major retailers show that the Christmas
shopping season wasn't as strong as many had expected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
