<HEADLINE> Clinton Extends U.S. Sanctions on Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Thursday extended U.S. sanctions on Libya on the ground of what
he said was the crisis between the United States and Libya not
being resolved.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in a letter to Congress that he was continuing the
sanctions, first imposed by former President Ronald Reagan in
1986, because "the crisis between the United States and Libya...
has not been resolved."
</P>
<P>
"The government of Libya has continued its action and policies
in support of terrorism, despite the calls by the United Nations
Security Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton took the action before the sanctions would have expired
on January 7.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Libya executed six senior officers and two
civilians, sentenced to death by the Supreme Military Court on
charges that they had used equipment supplied by the U.S. Central
Intelligence Agency (CIA) to spy for the United States.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials dismissed the trial as a propaganda ploy.
</P>
<P>
"They look like a propaganda ploy for internal consumption,"
one official said.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns just asked
journalists not to believe everything Libya has said.
</P>
<P>
"We would not believe everything that they've saying in
public," he said, complaining that Libya has always used the
United States as "a convenient scapegoat." 
</P>
</TEXT>
