<HEADLINE> Cold Spell with Ice on Roads Takes 2 Lives in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The ice on roads and streets in
Yugoslavia on Thursday took two lives and left many people with
serious fractures and other injuries.
</P>
<P>
Milijan Maric, 34, and Zoran Blagojevic, 32, were killed when
their tractor overturned due to ice and deep snow in the village
of Gornji Branetici on Mount Suvobor in western Serbia, Tanjug
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
About 30 people with serious fractures and concussions sought
medical help in Belgrade in the morning hours alone, head of the
emergency ward at the Banjica Orthopedic-surgical Hospital, Prof.
Milenko Stevanovic, said.
</P>
<P>
Heavy snow covered most of Yugoslavia on the New Year's eve,
forcing many people to stay at home. Ice rain on Wednesday and
early Thursday made traffic even worse.
</P>
<P>
The situation was no better in the Banat and Backa regions in
Serbia's northern province of Vojvodina, which were hit by ice
rain in the afternoon, leaving many injured, Tanjug added.
</P>
<P>
Floating ice covers 40 percent of the Danube river at the city
of Novi Sad, the capital city of Vojvodina, but did not affect the
navigation on the river.
</P>
<P>
Snow and ice on roads have slowed down the traffic across
Yugoslavia and made winter gear a must on roads in high parts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
