<HEADLINE> NATO to Seize Unregistered Muslim Army Munitions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The NATO-led Stabilization
Force (SFOR) said Thursday it would confiscate tank ammunition
donated to the Muslim-Croat Federation Army within a U.S. military
aid program because the ammunition had not been properly
registered.
</P>
<P>
SFOR spokesman Tony White said SFOR troops discovered in a
storage site early this week 474 tank rounds which the Federation
army did not register, Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The tank rounds were found in the storage site in Koracina, 10
km northwest of Livno in western Bosnia, which was under SFOR's
British command, White said.
</P>
<P>
The 105 mm tank ammunition was delivered to the Federation last
month within the U.S.-sponsored train and equip program that aims
to bolster the Federation army.
</P>
<P>
SFOR troops in Bosnia strictly enforce peacetime rules which
require rival armies to fully register all weapons or ammunition
stored at designated depots, White said.
</P>
<P>
"If it's existing equipment or received through train and equip
(program) it doesn't make any difference," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
A Sarajevo spokesman for the train and equip program said
11,000 tank rounds for 45 U.S. tanks had been shipped to the
Federation and placed in storage sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
