<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Reiterates Plan to Pay U.N. Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government today
restated its plan to pay off its 1.3 billion U.S. dollars of debt
to the United Nations, but stressed its expectation for further
U.N. reforms.
</P>
<P>
"The United States government, the Clinton administration,
wants to pay off our debt to the United Nations," said State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
"None of us feel that it's appropriate for a power like the
United States to be, in effect, a deadbeat donor at the United
Nations," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
Burns took the opportunity to congratulate new U.N.
Secretary-General Koffi Annan on assuming his responsibilities and
said "the United States thinks very highly of him."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Burns said, "We expect from Secretary-General Koffi
Annan's leadership a resurgent effort and vigorous effort to slim
the United Nations, to make it more focused and more effective and
less bloated."
</P>
<P>
He said that his country will support further U.N. reforms.
"And as long as that continues, there's every reason for the
Congress and the executive branch here in our government to agree
that the necessary money should be appropriated to pay off that
debt," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
On the sum of the debt, Burns said that there must be some
controversy about whether it was 1.3 billion U.S. dollars or 1.5
billion U.S. dollars. But he said the figure should be around 1.3
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
