<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New UN Chief Wants Reform, Support of Member States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Koffi Annan, the new U.N.
secretary-general, began his first day of work on Thursday and
immediately pledged to reform the world body.
</P>
<P>
At the same time Annan, who was greeted by an honor of guard of
U.N. police and a cheering crowd, said he expected member states
to honor their commitments to the world organization.
</P>
<P>
"This is my first day. It is like the first day in school.
Everyone expects a lot from you and you get into it with
considerable trepidation," he told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
"But there is a lot to do. There is a lot good will. And we
have a lot of dedicated staff and member states have made it clear
that they want changes and they have given us unanimous support."
</P>
<P>
"And I think together we can achieve a lot, bring about the
reforms that are necessary, encourage the member states to work
together, to honor their commitment to the organization and
together work for changes that are required if we are to make the
United Nations as relevant as it ought to be as we move into the
21st century," he said.
</P>
<P>
The gray-bearded soft-spoken Annan, who was the
undersecretary-general for peacekeeping operations, is the seventh
U.N. Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
He is also the first from sub-Saharan Africa and the first to
have risen through the ranks of the U.N. bureaucracy. He succeeds
the 74-year-old Boutros-Ghali of Egypt, who left for his home on
Tuesday and intends to live in France for several months to write
a book on his years in the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
