<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Storms Lead to 14 Deaths, Heavy Damages in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- At least 14 people were
killed in Oregon and Washington and damages worth hundreds of
millions of dollars were reported in five states in Northwest U.S.
in the week-long snow-storms.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 counties in Washington, Oregon, California, Idaho
and Nevada have been declared disaster areas because of damage
from flooding, rain and snow, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
Melting snow pushed rivers out of their banks across the
Northwest today, forcing hundreds of people from their homes and
stranding 2,500 in Yosemite National Park, the Associated Press
said.
</P>
<P>
In Napa, California, the Napa River rose to more than a meter
above flood level Wednesday and more than 100 people were asked to
evacuate.
</P>
<P>
Near Guerneville, north of San Francisco, the muddy Russian
River rose Wednesday evening to nearly 13 meters, 4 meters above
flood stage.
</P>
<P>
In Nevada, up to 7 inches of rain around Reno caused the worst
flooding in the city in more than 40 years. Dozens of homes and
businesses were flooded by the Truckee River and hundreds of
people were evacuated.
</P>
<P>
The snowstorm left more than 250,000 Northern Californian
households without power last week and power outages still affect
13,000 Washington households today.
</P>
<P>
Weather forecast said that more rain was expected in central and
eastern Washington into the weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
